# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abolitionism-in-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The **Germantown Petition** was a protest by American Quaker settlers in Pennsylvania demanding the abolition of slavery, the first formal petition of its kind.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] It was authored by Francis Daniel Pastorius, the founder of Germantown, Pennsylvania, with support from several of the Original 13 settlers of Pennsylvania including Derick op den Graeff and Abraham op den Graeff, who signed it on behalf of the Germantown Meeting of the Religious Society of Friends.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] A highly controversial document, Friends forwarded it up the hierarchical chain of their administrative structure—monthly, quarterly, and yearly meetings—without either approving or rejecting it.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The petition effectively disappeared for 150 years into the Philadelphia Yearly Meeting's archives, but was republished in 1844 in support of abolitionism after its rediscovery by the Philadelphia antiquarian Nathan Kite.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The Pennsylvania Colony was founded in 1682 by William Penn as a place where people from any country and faith could settle, free from religious persecution.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In payment of a debt to Penn's father, Penn had received from King Charles II a large land grant west of New Jersey which Charles II named Pennsylvania after William's father, Admiral William Penn.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Penn had become a friend of George Fox, the founder of the Religious Society of Friends, who were pejoratively nicknamed "Quakers" because they described themselves as quaking and trembling in fear of the Lord.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Penn had converted to Quakerism and had been imprisoned several times for his beliefs.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Charles II allowed Penn to establish a proprietary colony where Penn appointed the governor and judges but established an otherwise democratic system of government with freedom of religion, fair trials, elected representatives, and separation of church and state.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] From 1660 to 1680, several Quakers including William Penn visited the United Provinces and the Rhine Valley of what would later become Germany, and organized gatherings where they preached the Quaker testimony.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Many people, including some who had been Mennonites in Krefeld and Kriegsheim (now part of the modern Mennonite congregation of Monsheim, Germany), in the German "Palatinate", converted to the new Quaker faith.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Among them was Francis Daniel Pastorius, a young German born near Würzburg to a family of elite officeholders.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] After training as an attorney, Pastorius sought spiritual release from his lucrative but uninspiring practice with the local gentry, and he turned inward looking for a philosophical purity in his life.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] He was attracted to Penn's colony as a place where religious freedom would allow him to start afresh a life free from "libertinism and sins of the European world".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Meanwhile, the Mennonites and Quakers in the Netherlands and along the Rhine Valley were often fined or imprisoned for publicly practicing a faith other than the officially recognized Calvinism, Catholicism, and Lutheranism.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In 1681, Penn invited immigrants from Europe to the new colony.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] He arrived in 1682, had the land surveyed, organized Philadelphia as a welcoming town laid out as a grid with many green spaces, and profited by selling lots.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Soon, the waterfront was a bustle of activity, town streets were laid out with houses built on narrow lots, and churches of several different faiths were established.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The town merchants traded with the largely Quaker colony of West Jersey.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The town and surrounding countryside prospered.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In 1683, Pastorius was delegated authority to purchase land in the new Pennsylvania colony by a group of men from Frankfurt who intended to emigrate.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] He traveled to Philadelphia in August 1683, having purchased a warrant from Penn's agent on behalf of the Frankfurt men who had supplied the funds.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In October, 1683, thirteen German-Dutch families from Krefeld in the Rhine Valley, including the Op den Graeffs, arrived with their own land claim.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Seizing upon a chance to create a viable German-speaking town, Pastorius negotiated with Penn to combine the two claims.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] As it turned out, the people from the Frankfurt Company never emigrated to the new colony, but more Quakers and Mennonites came from the Rhine valley and Pastorius's ambitious plan for a German-speaking town near Philadelphia grew and became real.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Pastorius had devised a simple plan for a town, with lots parceled out along one long main thoroughfare, where settlers could build their houses.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] He required land good for tilling because the emigrants would need to grow their own food to survive.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Pastorius and Penn became good friends, and they often discussed plans for the new settlement over dinner.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The land originally promised to Pastorius was supposed to be level and along a navigable river, and Pastorius had paid for 6,000 contiguous acres (24 km2).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] However a suitable tract of land near Philadelphia was unavailable on the Delaware River, because level ground there was valuable and most of it had already been sold.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Penn suggested land near the Schuylkill Falls, but it was too steep for Pastorius's plan, so as an alternative Penn suggested land a little further east, near the top of a gentle hill between two creeks, and Pastorius agreed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Germantown was thus founded along a Lenape trail four miles (6 km) north of Philadelphia, between the Wissahickon and Wingohocking Creeks.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Pastorius had the land surveyed, and over the first winter the families lived in downtown Philadelphia while struggling to clear the land for their makeshift log houses.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Germantown became a separate and self-sufficient town of Dutch and German speakers.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The thirteen original Krefelder families were Mennonites who had become Quakers in their native Holland before they arrived in the new Pennsylvania colony.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Because they had been persecuted in their own land on account of their beliefs they understood the value of a community founded on religious tolerance.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Unlike Pastorius, they were not wealthy, but were skilled craftsmen who knew they would have to work hard for a living.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] By trade they were carpenters, weavers, dyers, tailors, and shoemakers, so they were not fully prepared for the hard work of clearing the forest.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Over the first year, they cleared land and planted crops for food and flax for weaving.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] They set up looms and soon were producing linen cloth that sold widely throughout the colonies.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Some of the early settlers of Philadelphia and its surrounding towns were wealthy and purchased African slaves to work on their farms.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Although many such slave owners also had immigrated to escape religious persecution, they saw no contradiction in owning slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Although serfdom had already been abolished in Northwestern Europe by 1500, servitude was still ubiquitous, and sometimes under harsh conditions.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Many immigrants to the new colony were indentured servants, who had signed an agreement to work for several years in exchange for being transported via a passenger ship to the new colony.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Slavery was widespread in the American colonies, and local slave markets ensured the ease of purchasing slaves to the general populace.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The Atlantic slave trade was beginning to rapidly expand, and many settlers thought it necessary for economic growth in the colonies.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Many slave ship owners and captains made large profits transporting slaves from Africa to the Caribbean and mainland North America.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] William Penn oversaw the economic progress of his colony and once proudly declared that during the course of a year Philadelphia had received ten slave ships.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The first settlers of Germantown were soon joined by several more Quaker and Mennonite families from Kriegsheim (Monsheim), also in the Rhine valley, who were ethnic Germans but spoke a similar dialect to the Hollanders from Krefeld.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Some out of pragmatism attended the local Quaker meetings held in the newly built homes of immigrants, becoming involved and accepted in the Philadelphia Quaker community, and eventually joining as members.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] However, in several ways they felt themselves outsiders, which allowed them to question the social values in the nascent colony.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Some attended the Quaker meeting temporarily while they waited for a Mennonite minister to arrive, and then helped to build the first Mennonite Meetinghouse.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The town prospered and grew, and a Quaker meeting was organized at Thones Kunders's house, under the care of Dublin (Abington Meeting).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] By 1686, a Quaker meetinghouse was constructed near the current site of the Germantown Friends Meeting.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The German-Dutch settlers were unaccustomed to owning slaves, although from the shortage of labor they understood why slavery was required to ensure the economic prosperity of the colony.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Slaves and indentured servants were a valuable asset for a farmer because they were not paid.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Yet the German-Dutch settlers refused to buy slaves themselves and quickly saw the contradiction in the slave trade and in farmers who forced people to work.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Although in their native Germany and Holland the Krefelders had been persecuted because of their beliefs, only people who had been convicted of a crime could be forced to work in servitude.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In what turned out to be a revolutionary leap of insight, the Germantowners saw a fundamental similarity between the right to be free from persecution on account of their beliefs and the right to be free from being forced to work against their will.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In 1688, five years after Germantown was founded, Pastorius, Garret Hendericks, Derick op den Graeff, and Abraham op den Graeff petitioned the Dublin Quaker meeting.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The men gathered at Thones Kunders's house and wrote a petition based upon the Bible's Golden Rule, "Do unto others as you would have them do unto you", urging the meeting to abolish slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] It is an unconventional text in that it avoids the expected salutation to fellow Quakers and does not contain references to Jesus and God.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] It argues that every human, regardless of belief, color, or ethnicity, has rights that should not be violated.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Throughout the petition the reference to the Golden Rule is used to argue against slavery and for universal human rights.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] On first reading, the argument presented in the petition seems indirect.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Nowhere is the meeting specifically asked to condemn the practice of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Instead, in reference to the Golden Rule, the four men ask why Christians are allowed to buy and own slaves, almost in mock sarcasm, to get the slave owners to see their point.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In doing so, it arguably was very successful, but it would be easy to miss the sophistication of their argument.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] They emphatically argue that in their society the capture and sale of ordinary people as slaves, where husband, wife and children are separated, would not be tolerated, again referring to the Golden Rule.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The four men also assert that according to the Golden Rule, the slaves would have the right to revolt, and that inviting more people to the new land would be difficult if prospective settlers saw the contradiction inherent in slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In mentioning the possibility of a slave revolt, they clearly were suggesting to that slavery would discourage potential settlers from emigrating to the American colonies.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In the Caribbean colonies there had been many slave revolts over several decades, so the possibility was real.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] However, the power of the argument for potential settlers from Europe was more than the fear of a revolt—it was that any such revolt would be justifiable according to the Golden Rule.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] This logic strengthened the newly defined universal rights, which applied to all humans, not just the "civilized".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The petition has several examples of such counter-intuitive but forceful arguments to push the slave-owning reader off his balance.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The petition contains several points of difficulty for the reader unfamiliar with history.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] First, the petition's grammar seems unusual today but reflects the Krefelders' incomplete knowledge of English as well as typical pre-modern use of variable spelling.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The original wording includes "ye", which is a contraction of the word "the", and might be confused with the second person plural "ye" that was in wide use at the time.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Second, the petition mentions the Turks as an example of a people who might take someone on a ship into slavery in the Ottoman Empire.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The four men were referring to the widely known stories of Barbary pirates who had established outposts on the coast of North Africa and for hundreds of years had plundered ships.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] After the Muslims were driven out of Spain in 1492, they raided the Spanish coast and the Spanish countered with more attacks.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The Barbary pirates in the period (1518–1587) were allied with the Ottoman authorities and captured slaves to be brought back to North Africa or Turkey.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Thus in their early period, their motivation was political.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In the later period during the 17th century, the North African pirate communities became more independent and lived mainly on plunder so the motivation for piracy was mainly economic.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In that period up to 20,000 captured Christians were said to be kept as slaves in Algiers.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The slave raiders traveled throughout the Mediterranean Sea and the North Atlantic, often taking slaves from Italy and Spain, but ranging as far north as Ireland (see sack of Baltimore).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Among the Barbary pirates were renegades from Northern Europe who had converted to Islam.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Some English, French, and Germans were allowed to pay their way out of slavery and so brought back the stories of marauding pirates capturing slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The petition's mention of this point, then, is another example of their sophisticated reasoning.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The widely circulated stories of slavery on the Barbary Coast were true, for Europeans had been the prey of political enemies and renegades who had captured them as slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Indeed, in the year that the petition was written, a number of Quakers were enslaved in Morocco, including the captain of the ship that had brought Pastorius and his compatriots to Pennsylvania.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] This analogy in the first paragraph of the petition cast the Atlantic slave trade in a questionable light.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The four authors expressed their belief that slaves had social and political equality with ordinary citizens.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Third, the petition refers to the black slaves as "negers", which was a German and Dutch word meaning black or negro.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In its 1688 usage the term was simply descriptive and not in any way derogatory.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Throughout the petition the four men show respect for enslaved people and declare them equals.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The four men - Pastorius, Garret Hendericks, and both Op den Graeff brothers - presented their petition at the local monthly meeting at Dublin (Abington), but it is not clear what they expected to happen.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] It is reasonably certain that Derick op den Graeff read it at the meeting to Richard Worrall and he is the only name mentioned in connection with the presentation at the annual meeting.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Although they were accepted in the Quaker community, they were outsiders who could not speak or write fluently in English, and they also had a fresh view of slavery that was unique to Germantown.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] They must have understood from the beginning that it would be difficult to force the whole colony to abolish slavery, as it was generally believed that the colony's prosperity depended on slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] It is not clear whether the four men expected the local meeting to affirm their view, because they knew that nearby meetings might not in be in agreement, and consequences would be far-reaching.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The meeting decided that although the issue was fundamental and just, it was too difficult and consequential for them to judge, and would need to be considered further.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In the usual manner the meeting sent the petition on to the Philadelphia Quarterly Meeting, where it was again considered and sent on to the Philadelphia Yearly Meeting, held in Burlington, New Jersey.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Realizing that the abolition of slavery would have a wide and overreaching impact on the entire colony, none of the meetings wanted to pass judgment on such a "weighty matter".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The Philadelphia Yearly Meeting minuted that they would send the petition to London Yearly Meeting, without mentioning whether they actually did so, and on this point no direct evidence has been discovered.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The minutes of the London Yearly Meeting do not mention the petition directly, apparently skirting the issue.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The practice of slavery continued and was tolerated in Quaker society in the years immediately following the 1688 petition.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Some of the authors continued to protest against slavery, but for a decade their efforts were rejected.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Germantown continued to prosper, growing in population and economic strength, becoming widely known for the quality of its products such as paper and woven cloth.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Eventually several of the original Krefelders rejoined the Mennonites and moved away from Germantown at least in part because of their insistence not to side with slave owners.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Several other petitions and protests were written by Quakers against slavery in the next several decades, but were based on racist or practical arguments of inferiority and intolerance.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Some of the protests became entangled with politics and theology and as a result were dismissed by the Philadelphia Yearly Meeting, confusing the issue.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Almost three decades passed before another Quaker petition against slavery was written with sophistication comparable to the Germantown 1688 petition.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] However, the Germantowners' condemnation of slavery continued, and their moral leadership on the issue influenced Quaker abolitionists and Philadelphia society.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Gradually over the next century, due to the efforts of many dedicated Quakers such as Benjamin Lay, John Woolman, and Anthony Benezet, Quakers became convinced of the essential wrongness of the institution of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Many of the Quaker abolitionists published their articles anonymously in Benjamin Franklin's newspaper.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] In 1776 a proclamation was written by Philadelphia Yearly Meeting banning the owning of slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] By that time, many Quaker monthly meetings in the Delaware Valley were attempting to help freed slaves by providing funds for them to start businesses and encouraging them to attend Quaker meetings and educate their children.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Villages were set up in places such as Lima, Pennsylvania, where released slaves could settle with support from local families involved in the anti-slavery movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The well-known Van Leer family helped set up lots in Lima, for newly freed slaves and people who would support them.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The 1688 petition was the first American document of its kind that made a plea for equal human rights for everyone.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The 1688 petition was set aside and forgotten until 1844 when it was re-discovered and became a focus of the burgeoning abolitionist movement in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] After a century of public exposure, it was misplaced and once more re-discovered in March 2005 in the vault at Arch Street Friends Meeting House.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] At that time, it was in deteriorating condition, with tears at the edges, paper tape covering voids and handwriting where the petition had originally been folded, and its oak gall ink slowly fading into gray.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] To preserve the document for future generations, it was treated at the Conservation Center for Art and Historic Artifacts (CCAHA) in downtown Philadelphia.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] CCAHA conservator Morgan Zinsmeister removed previous repairs and reduced centuries of old and discolored adhesives with various poultices and enzymatic solutions.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Acidity and discoloration in the paper were reduced through aqueous treatment.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Repairs were made with acrylic-toned Japanese papers that were carefully applied to bridge the voids.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Finally, the petition was photographed at high resolution and then encapsulated along its edges (not laminated) between sheets of inert polyester film.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] The petition was shown at an exhibit of original rare American documents at the National Constitution Center on Independence Mall in the summer of 2007.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] It currently resides at Haverford College Quaker and Special Collections, the joint repository (with Friends Historical Library of Swarthmore College) for the records of Philadelphia Yearly Meeting.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1688-germantown-quaker-petition-against-slavery] Today, the 1688 petition is for many a powerful reminder about the basis for freedom and equality for all.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 35th United States Congress and the presidency of the United States, to serve from 1857 until 1861.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] The elections took place during a major national debate over slavery, with the issue of "Bleeding Kansas" taking center stage.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Along with the 1854 elections, these elections occurred during the transitional period immediately preceding the Third Party System.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Old party lines were broken; new party alignments along sectional lines were in the process of formation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] The Republican Party absorbed the Northern anti-slavery representatives who had been elected in 1854 under the "Opposition Party" ticket (consisting largely of former Whigs) as the second-most powerful party in Congress.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Minnesota and Oregon joined the union before the next election, and elected their respective congressional delegations to the 35th Congress.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] In the presidential election, Democratic former Secretary of State James Buchanan defeated Republican General John Fremont and the American Party candidate, former President Millard Fillmore.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Buchanan swept the South and split the North with Fremont, while Fillmore won Maryland.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Buchanan had defeated incumbent President Franklin Pierce (the first elected president to lose his party's presidential nomination) and Senator Stephen A.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Douglas of Illinois on the 17th ballot at the 1856 Democratic National Convention.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Fremont defeated Supreme Court Justice John McLean at the 1856 Republican National Convention to take the Republican nomination.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Fillmore's third-party candidacy took over twenty percent of the popular vote, the best popular vote showing by a third party until Theodore Roosevelt's 1912 candidacy.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] In the House, the Democratic Party won several seats to take the plurality, but narrowly missed taking the majority.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] The Republican Party established itself as the second-largest party in the House, replacing the Opposition Party.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] The American Party lost numerous seats, but continued to maintain a presence in the House.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] Democrat James Lawrence Orr won election as Speaker of the House.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] In the Senate, Democrats made minor gains, maintaining their commanding majority.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1856-united-states-elections] The Republican Party replaced the Opposition Party as the second-largest party, while the American Party picked up a small number of seats.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A United States presidential election was held on November 6, 1860.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican Party ticket of Abraham Lincoln and Hannibal Hamlin emerged victorious.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 1860, the United States was divided over the issue of slavery, and four major political parties had nominated candidates in the 1860 presidential election.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent president James Buchanan, a Democrat, did not seek re-election.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The anti-slavery Republican Party nominated Abraham Lincoln, who previously had been a one-term Whig Representative from Illinois, for president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Its platform promised not to interfere with slavery in the states where it existed, but opposed its extension into the territories.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party, which sought to avoid disunion by resolving divisions over slavery with some new compromise.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 Constitutional Union Convention put forward former Tennessee Senator John Bell for president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the 1860 Democratic National Convention adjourned without agreeing on a nominee, a second convention nominated Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas as the Northern Democratic presidential candidate.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas's support for the concept of popular sovereignty, which called for each territory's settlers to decide the status of slavery within the territory, alienated many radical pro-slavery Southern Democrats.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With President Buchanan's support, Southern Democrats held their own convention, nominating Vice President John C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received a majority in the Electoral College, with all his Electoral College votes coming from Northern states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He prevailed in 18 states, won 180 electoral votes, and received 39.7 percent of the popular vote.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas won the second-highest popular vote total, but won only the state of Missouri; he was the only candidate in the 1860 election to win electoral votes in both free and slave states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge won 11 states, finishing third in the popular vote, while Bell finished fourth in the popular vote and won the electoral votes of the states of Kentucky, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the last presidential election in which it appointed its presidential electors at the discretion of the state legislature rather than by popular vote (and was the only state to do so), the presidential electors of South Carolina cast their ballots for Breckinridge.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 election was the first of six consecutive Republican presidential victories.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's election as the first Republican president served as the main catalyst for Southern secession and the American Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His election motivated seven Southern states, all of which had voted for Breckinridge, to secede from the United States before Lincoln's inauguration on March 4, 1861.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Civil War began less than two months after the inauguration with the Battle of Fort Sumter, after which four more slave states seceded.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 presidential election conventions were unusually tumultuous, particularly because a split in the Democratic Party had led to both Northern and Southern party conventions.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican National Convention met in mid-May 1860 after the Democrats had been forced to adjourn their convention in Charleston.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With the Democrats in disarray and a sweep of the Northern states possible, the Republicans felt confident going into their convention in Chicago.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seward from New York was considered the front-runner, followed by Salmon P.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase from Ohio, and Missouri's Edward Bates.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Abraham Lincoln from Illinois was less well-known and was not considered to have a good chance against Seward.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seward had been governor and senator of New York, and was an able politician with a Whig background.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clay, and Benjamin Wade, who might be able to win if the convention deadlocked.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the convention developed, however, it was revealed that frontrunners Seward, Chase, and Bates had each alienated factions of the Republican Party.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Seward had been painted as a radical, and his speeches on slavery predicted inevitable conflict, which spooked moderate delegates.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also was firmly opposed to nativism, which further weakened his position.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He had also been abandoned by his longtime friend and political ally Horace Greeley, publisher of the influential *New-York Tribune*.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase, a former Democrat, had alienated many of the former Whigs by his coalition with the Democrats in the late 1840s.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He had also opposed tariffs demanded by Pennsylvania and even had opposition from his own delegation from Ohio.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Chase's firm anti-slavery stance made him popular with the Radical Republicans; but what he offered in policy, he lacked in charisma and political acumen.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The conservative Bates was an unlikely candidate but found support from Horace Greeley, who sought any chance to defeat Seward, with whom he now had a bitter feud.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was not unknown; he had gained prominence in the 1858 Lincoln–Douglas debates and had represented Illinois in the House of Representatives.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln had been quietly eyeing a run since the debates, ensuring that they were widely published and that a biography of himself was published.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He gained great renown with his acclaimed February 1860 Cooper Union speech, which may have ensured him the nomination, even though he had not yet announced his intention to run.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Delivered in Seward's home state and attended by Greeley, Lincoln used the speech to show that the Republican Party was a party of moderates, not crazed fanatics, as Southerners and Democrats claimed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Afterward, Lincoln was in much demand for speaking engagements.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the convention approached, Lincoln did not campaign actively, as the "office was expected to seek the man".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] So it did at the Illinois state convention, a week before the national convention.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Young politician Richard Oglesby found several fence rails that Lincoln may have split as a youngster and paraded them into the convention with a banner that proclaimed Lincoln to be "The Rail Candidate" for president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received a thunderous ovation, surpassing his and his political allies' expectations.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's campaign managers had printed and distributed thousands of fake convention admission tickets to Lincoln supporters to ensure and increase the crowd's support.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Even with such support from his home state, Lincoln faced a difficult task if he was to win the nomination.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He set about ensuring that he was the second choice of most delegates, realizing that the first round of voting at the convention was unlikely to produce a clear winner.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He engineered that the convention would be held in Chicago, which would be inherently friendly to the Illinois-based Lincoln.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also made sure that the Illinois delegation would vote as a bloc for him.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln did not attend the convention in person and left the task of delegate wrangling to several close friends.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The first round of voting predictably produced a lead for Seward, but not a majority, with Lincoln in second place.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The second round eliminated most of the minor contenders, with voters switching mostly to Seward or Lincoln.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The convention remained deadlocked, however, and successful political maneuvering by Lincoln's delegates persuaded some delegates to abandon Seward in favor of Lincoln.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's combination of a moderate stance on slavery, his position on economic issues, his western origins, and his strong oratory proved to be exactly what the delegates wanted in a president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the third ballot on May 18, Lincoln secured the presidential nomination overwhelmingly.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Hannibal Hamlin from Maine was nominated for vice president, defeating Clay.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party platform promised not to interfere with slavery in the states, but opposed slavery in the territories.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The platform promised tariffs protecting industry and workers, a Homestead Act granting free farmland in the West to settlers, and the funding of a transcontinental railroad.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There was no mention of Mormonism (which had been condemned in the Party's 1856 platform), the Fugitive Slave Act, personal liberty laws, or the Dred Scott decision.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While the Seward forces were disappointed at the nomination of a little-known western upstart, they rallied behind Lincoln, while abolitionists were angry at the selection of a moderate and had little faith in Lincoln.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas from Illinois, James Guthrie from Kentucky, Robert Mercer Taliaferro Hunter from Virginia, Joseph Lane from Oregon, Daniel S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Dickinson from New York, and Andrew Johnson from Tennessee, while three other candidates, Isaac Toucey from Connecticut, James Pearce from Maryland, and Jefferson Davis from Mississippi (the future president of the Confederate States) also received votes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas, a moderate on the slavery issue who favored "popular sovereignty", was ahead on the first ballot, but was 56½ votes short of securing the nomination.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the 57th ballot, with Douglas still ahead, but 51½ votes short of the nomination, the exhausted and desperate delegates agreed on May 3 to cease voting and adjourn the convention.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While some considered Horatio Seymour a compromise candidate for the national Democratic nomination at the reconvening convention in Baltimore, Seymour wrote a letter to the editor of his local newspaper declaring unreservedly that he was not a candidate for either spot on the ticket.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After two ballots - the 59th ballot overall - the remaining Democrats nominated Stephen A.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The election would now pit Lincoln against his longtime political rival, whom Lincoln had lost to in the Illinois senate race just two years earlier.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] That two candidates were from Illinois showed the importance of the West in the election.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While Benjamin Fitzpatrick from Alabama was nominated for vice president, he refused the nomination.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the convention concluded with no vice presidential nominee, Douglas offered the vice presidential nomination to Herschel V.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The southern delegates walked out of Institute Hall on April 30, moving at first to the Saint Andrews Hall, then to Military Hall on May 1st.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On May 3rd, when the northern delegates left Charleston, the southern delegates left as well, reconvening at Metropolitan Hall in Richmond, Virginia on June 11.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When the Democrats reconvened at Front Street Theater in Baltimore, they rejoined (except South Carolina and Florida, who had stayed in Richmond).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When the convention seated two replacement delegations on June 18, they walked out again or boycotted the convention, accompanied by nearly all other Southern delegates and erstwhile Convention chair Caleb Cushing, a New Englander and former member of Franklin Pierce's cabinet.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This larger group met immediately in Baltimore's Maryland Institute Hall, with Cushing again presiding.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They adopted the pro-slavery platform rejected at Charleston, and nominated Vice President John C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge for president, and Senator Joseph Lane from Oregon for vice president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Yancey and some (less than half) of the bolters - almost entirely from the Lower South - met on June 28 at Metropolitan Hall in Richmond, along with the South Carolina and Florida delegations, at a convention that affirmed the nominations of Breckinridge and Lane.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Besides the Democratic parties in the Southern states, the Breckinridge/Lane ticket was also supported by the Buchanan administration.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Buchanan's own continued prestige in his home state of Pennsylvania ensured that Breckinridge would be the principal Democratic candidate in that populous state.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge was the last sitting vice president nominated for president until Richard Nixon in 1960.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Constitutional Union Party was formed by remnants of both the defunct Know Nothing and Whig parties who were unwilling to join either the Republicans or the Democrats.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The new party's members hoped to stave off Southern secession by avoiding the slavery issue.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They met in the Eastside District Courthouse of Baltimore and nominated John Bell from Tennessee for president over Governor Sam Houston of Texas on the second ballot.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Edward Everett was nominated for vice president at the convention on May 9, 1860, one week before Lincoln.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John Bell was a former Whig who had opposed the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the Lecompton Constitution.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Edward Everett had been president of Harvard University and Secretary of State in the Millard Fillmore administration.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Radical Abolitionist Party was a remnant of the Liberty Party that formed after most former Liberty and Free Soil Party members joined the Republicans in the 1850s.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A convention of one hundred delegates was held in Convention Hall, Syracuse, New York, on August 29, 1860.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Delegates were in attendance from New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Michigan, Illinois, Ohio, Kentucky, and Massachusetts.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gerrit Smith, a prominent abolitionist and the 1848 presidential nominee of the original Liberty Party, had sent a letter in which he stated that his health had been so poor that he had not been able to be away from home since 1858.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, he remained popular in the party because he had helped inspire some of John Brown's supporters at the Raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In his letter, Smith donated $50 to pay for the printing of ballots in the various states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There was quite a spirited contest between the friends of Gerrit Smith and William Goodell in regard to the nomination for the presidency.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In spite of his professed ill health, Gerrit Smith was nominated for president and Samuel McFarland from Pennsylvania was nominated for vice president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In Ohio, Illinois, and Indiana, slates of presidential electors pledged to Smith and McFarland ran with the name of the Union Party.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They received a total of 176 votes in the general election, 0.004% of the total.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The People's Party was a loose association of the supporters of Governor Samuel Houston.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On April 20, 1860, the party held what it termed a national convention to nominate Houston for president on the San Jacinto Battlefield in Texas.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Houston's supporters at the gathering did not nominate a vice presidential candidate, since they expected later gatherings to carry out that function.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Later mass meetings were held in northern cities, such as New York City on May 30, 1860, but they too failed to nominate a vice presidential candidate.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Houston, never enthusiastic about running for the presidency, soon became convinced that he had no chance of winning and that his candidacy would only make it easier for the Republican candidate to win.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He withdrew from the race on August 16, and urged the formation of a Unified "Union" ticket in opposition to Lincoln.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In their campaigning, Bell and Douglas both claimed that disunion would not necessarily follow a Lincoln election.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, loyal army officers in Virginia, Kansas and South Carolina warned Lincoln of military preparations to the contrary.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mexican War hero Winfield Scott suggested to Lincoln that he assume the powers of a commander-in-chief before inauguration.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, historian Bruce Chadwick observes that Lincoln and his advisors ignored the widespread alarms and threats of secession as mere election trickery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Indeed, voting in the South was not as monolithic as the Electoral College map would make it seem.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Economically, culturally, and politically, the South was made up of three regions.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the states of the Upper South, also known as the Border South (Delaware, Maryland, Kentucky, and Missouri), unionist popular votes were scattered among Lincoln, Douglas, and Bell, to form a majority in all four.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the four Middle South states, there was a unionist majority divided between Douglas and Bell in Virginia and Tennessee; in North Carolina and Arkansas, the unionist (Bell and Douglas) vote approached a majority.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In three of the seven Deep South states, unionists (Bell and Douglas) won divided majorities in Georgia and Louisiana and neared it in Alabama.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge convincingly carried only four of the seven states of the Deep South (South Carolina, Florida, Mississippi, and Texas).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Deep South states had the largest enslaved populations, and consequently the smallest enfranchised free white populations.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Among the slave states, the three states with the highest voter turnouts voted the most one-sided.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Texas, with five percent of the total wartime South's population, voted 75 percent Breckinridge.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kentucky and Missouri, with one-fourth of the total population, voted 73 percent pro-Union Bell, Douglas and Lincoln.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In comparison, the other six states of the Deep South made up one-fourth of the Confederate voting population; this was split 57 percent for Breckinridge versus 43 percent for the two pro-union candidates.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The four states that were admitted to the Confederacy after Fort Sumter held almost half its population, and voted a narrow combined majority of 53 percent for the pro-union candidates.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the eleven states that would later declare their secession from the Union and be controlled by Confederate armies, ballots for Lincoln were cast only in Virginia, where he received 1,929 votes (1.15 percent of the total).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The vast majority of the votes Lincoln received were cast in border counties of what would soon become West Virginia – the future state accounted for 1,832 of Lincoln's 1,929 votes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received no votes at all in 121 of the state's at-the-time 145 counties (including 31 of the 50 that would form West Virginia), received a single vote in three counties and received ten or fewer votes in nine of the 24 counties where he polled votes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hancock County (Virginia's northernmost at the time) returned Lincoln's best result – he polled over 40% of the vote there and finished in second place (Lincoln polled only eight votes fewer than Breckinridge).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the 97 votes cast for Lincoln in the state's post-1863 boundaries, 93 were polled in four counties along the Potomac River and four were tallied in the coastal city of Portsmouth.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Lincoln received no votes in 10 Southern states, this was not because he was removed from the ballot in those states, but rather due to the Republican Party's absence in those states (parties rather than states printed ballots in that era).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] One key difference between modern elections and those of the mid-nineteenth century is that at the time the state did not print and distribute ballots.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Moreover, since voters did not choose the president directly, but rather presidential electors, the only way for a voter to meaningfully support a particular candidate for president was cast a ballot for citizens of his state who would have pledged to vote for the candidate in the Electoral College.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In ten southern slave states, no citizen would publicly pledge to vote for Abraham Lincoln, so citizens there had no legal means to vote for the Republican nominee.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In most of Virginia, no publisher would print ballots for Lincoln's pledged electors.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the four slave states that did not secede Lincoln came third in Delaware and fourth in Missouri, Kentucky and Maryland.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Within the fifteen slave states, Lincoln won only two counties out of 996, Missouri's St.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the 1856 election, the Republican candidate for president had received no votes at all in twelve of the fourteen slave states with a popular vote (these being the same states as in the 1860 election, plus Missouri and Virginia).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The election was held on Tuesday, November 6, 1860, and was noteworthy for the exaggerated sectionalism and voter enthusiasm in a country that was soon to dissolve into civil war.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Voter turnout was 81.2%, the highest in American history up to that time, and the second-highest overall (exceeded only in the election of 1876).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] 31.5% of the voting age population voted.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Since Andrew Jackson had won re-election in 1832, all six subsequent presidents had only won one term, while the last four of those had won with a popular vote under 51 percent.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln won the Electoral College with less than 40 percent of the popular vote nationwide by carrying states above the Mason–Dixon line and north of the Ohio River, plus the states of California and Oregon in the Far West.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Unlike every preceding president-elect, Lincoln did not carry even one slave state; he instead carried all eighteen free states exclusively.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received no votes in ten Southern states because the Republican Party was absent in those states (parties rather than states printed ballots in that era).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There were no ballots distributed for Lincoln in ten of the Southern states: Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This withheld 61 potential electoral votes from Lincoln, a fifth of what was the total 303 available to the other candidates.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In a similar divide between North and South electors, Breckenridge carried nine of the ten states that withheld Lincoln from the ballot, the exception being Tennessee.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It should be further noted that, prior to the introduction of the secret ballot in the 1880s, the concept of ballot access did not exist in the sense it does today: there was no standardized state-issued ballot for a candidate to "appear" on.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Instead, presidential ballots were printed and distributed by agents of the candidates and their parties, who organized slates of would-be electors publicly pledged to vote for a particular candidate.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln won the second-lowest share of the popular vote among all winning presidential candidates in U.S. history.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's share of the popular vote would likely have been even lower if there had been a popular vote in South Carolina, though conversely it would likely have been marginally higher had Republican ballots been widely available to voters throughout the Southern States.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican victory resulted from the concentration of votes in the free states, which together controlled a majority of the presidential electors.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Wide Awakes young Republican men's organization massively expanded registered voter lists, and population increases in the free states had far exceeded those seen in the slave states for many years before the election of 1860, hence free states dominated in the Electoral College.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gasconade County, Missouri has voted for a Republican presidential candidate in every election from 1860 on, which, as of 2024, makes it the longest Republican winning streak in presidential elections in the nation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite Lincoln's commanding victory, this was the first election in American history in which the winner failed to win a majority of votes in his home county, with Lincoln narrowly losing Sangamon County, Illinois to Douglas, his main opponent in the North.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Regardless, Lincoln won absolute majorities (>50%) in enough states, that if he lost all states that he took with pluralities, he still would have received enough electoral votes to win.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In short, even if Ranked-Choice Voting, or any other runoff system had been in effect in every state, Lincoln still would have won on the first round.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In New York, Pennsylvania, and New Jersey, where anti-Lincoln votes were combined into fusion tickets, Lincoln still won New York and Pennsylvania and split New Jersey.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, a shift of 25,000 votes to the fusion ticket in New York would have left Lincoln with 145 electoral votes — seven votes short of winning the Electoral College — and forced a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Alternatively, a shift of only 15,400 votes over California, Illinois, Minnesota, New Jersey, Oregon, and Rhode Island would have left Lincoln short of the necessary 152 electoral votes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the five states that Lincoln failed to carry, he received 20 percent of the vote in only one (Delaware) and 10 percent of the vote in one more (Missouri).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Like Lincoln, Breckinridge and Bell won no electoral votes outside of their respective sections.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While Bell retired to his family business, quietly supporting his state's secession, Breckinridge served as a Confederate general.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He finished second in the Electoral College with 72 votes, carrying eleven of fifteen slave states (including South Carolina, whose electors were chosen by the state legislature, not popular vote).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge stood a distant third in national popular vote at eighteen percent, but accrued 50 to 75 percent in the first seven states that would form the Confederate States of America.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He took nine of the eleven states that eventually joined, plus the border slave states of Delaware and Maryland, losing only Virginia and Tennessee.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge received very little support in the free states, showing some strength only in California, Oregon, Pennsylvania, and Connecticut.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bell carried three slave states (Tennessee, Kentucky, and Virginia) and lost Maryland by only 722 votes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, he finished a remarkable second in all slave states won by Breckinridge or Douglas.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He won 45 to 47 percent in Maryland, Tennessee, and North Carolina and canvassed respectably with 36 to 40 percent in Missouri, Arkansas, Louisiana, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bell himself had hoped that he would take over the former support of the extinct Whig Party in free states, but the majority of this support went to Lincoln.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Thus, except for running mate Everett's home state of Massachusetts, and California, Bell received even less support in the free states than did Breckinridge, and consequently came in last in the national popular vote, at 12.62%.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas was the only candidate who won electoral votes in both slave and free states (free New Jersey and slave Missouri).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His support was the most widespread geographically; he finished second behind Lincoln in the popular vote with 29.52%, but last in the Electoral College.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His 12 electoral votes are the lowest for a Democrat in history.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas attained a 28 to 47% share in the states of the Mid-Atlantic, Midwest, and Trans-Mississippi West, but slipped to 19 to 39% in New England.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Outside his regional section, Douglas took 15 to 17% of the popular vote total in the slave states of Kentucky, Alabama, and Louisiana, then 10 percent or less in the nine remaining slave states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Douglas, in his "Norfolk Doctrine", reiterated in North Carolina, promised to keep the Union together by coercion if states proceeded to secede: the popular vote for Lincoln and Douglas combined was 69.17% of the turnout.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 Republican ticket was the first successful national ticket that did not feature a Southerner, and the election marked the end of Southern political dominance in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Between 1789 and 1860, Southerners had been president for two-thirds of the era, and had held the offices of Speaker of the House and President pro tempore of the Senate during much of that time.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Moreover, since 1791, Southerners had constituted a majority of the Supreme Court.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p01] (b) *The option of Lincoln was absent from 20.13% of ballots across ten states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Lincoln's victory and imminent inauguration as president was the immediate cause for declarations of secession by seven Southern states (South Carolina, Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas) from 20 December 1860 to 1 February 1861.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They then formed the Confederate States of America.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On 9 February 1861, Jefferson Davis was elected president of the Confederacy.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All of the secessionist activity was motivated by fear for the institution of slavery in the South.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] If the President (and, by extension, the appointed federal officials in the South, such as district attorneys, marshals, postmasters, and judges) opposed slavery, it might collapse.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There were fears that abolitionist agents would infiltrate the South and foment slave insurrections.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] (The noted secessionist William Lowndes Yancey, speaking at New York's Cooper Institute in October 1860, asserted that with abolitionists in power, "Emissaries will percolate between master [and] slave as water between the crevices of rocks underground.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They will be found everywhere, with strychnine to put in our wells.") Less radical Southerners thought that with Northern antislavery dominance of the federal government, slavery would eventually be abolished, regardless of present constitutional limits.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bertram Wyatt-Brown argues that secessionists desired independence as necessary for their honor.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They could no longer tolerate Northern state attitudes that regarded slave ownership as a great sin and Northern politicians who insisted on stopping the spread of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Another bloc of Southerners resented Northern criticism of slavery and restrictions on slavery but opposed secession as dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, the "conditional Unionists" also hoped that when faced with secession, Northerners would stifle anti-slavery rhetoric and accept pro-slavery rules for the territories.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was that group that prevented immediate secession in Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Arkansas when Lincoln took office on March 4, 1861.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He took no action against the secessionists in the seven "Confederate" states, but also declared that secession had no legal validity and refused to surrender federal property in those states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] (He also reiterated his opposition to slavery anywhere in the territories.) Preparing to form an army, on 6 March 1861 Davis called for 100,000 volunteers to serve for twelve months.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The political standoff continued until mid-April, when Davis ordered Confederate troops to bombard and capture Fort Sumter.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Lincoln then called for troops to put down rebellion, which wiped out the possibility that the crisis could be resolved by compromise.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nearly all "conditional Unionists" joined the secessionists, including for example presidential candidate John Bell of the Constitutional Union Party, whose home state of Tennessee was the last to secede.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Virginia convention and the reconvened Arkansas convention both declared secession, as did the legislatures of Tennessee and North Carolina; all four states joined the Confederacy.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Missouri and Kentucky stayed in the United States, but had unrecognized dual governments.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After the Civil War begun, Douglas then threw his support behind Lincoln and undertook a tour to bolster support for the Union, making visits to Virginia, Ohio and Illinois.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Douglas declared "There are no neutrals, only patriots and traitors".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1860-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, three months after Lincoln's inauguration, Douglas contracted typhoid fever and died in Chicago on June 3, 1861.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 8, 1864, near the end of the American Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President Abraham Lincoln of the National Union Party easily defeated the Democratic nominee, former General George B.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, by a wide margin of 212–21 in the electoral college, with 55% of the popular vote.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For the election, the Republican Party and some Democrats created the National Union Party, especially to attract War Democrats.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite some intra-party opposition from Salmon Chase and the Radical Republicans, Lincoln won his party's nomination at the 1864 National Union National Convention.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than re-nominate Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, the convention selected Andrew Johnson of Tennessee, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats were divided between the Copperheads, who favored immediate peace with the Confederacy, and War Democrats, who supported the war.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 Democratic National Convention nominated McClellan, a War Democrat, but adopted a platform advocating peace with the Confederacy, which McClellan rejected, although his running mate George H.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] While the Confederacy seemed to have survival potential in summer 1864, it was visibly collapsing by election day in November.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his early fears of defeat, Lincoln won strong majorities in the popular and electoral vote, partly as a result of the recent Union victory at the Battle of Atlanta.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War was still raging, no electoral votes were counted from any of the eleven southern states that had joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's re-election ensured that he would preside over the successful conclusion of the Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's victory made him the first president to win re-election since Andrew Jackson in 1832, as well as the first Northern president to ever win re-election.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was assassinated six weeks into his second term.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was succeeded by his vice president, Andrew Johnson, who favored quick restoration of the seceded states to the Union without protection for the former slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This led to conflict with the Republican-dominated Congress, culminating in Johnson's impeachment by the House of Representatives in 1868; he was acquitted in the Senate by one vote.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election took place during the American Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] According to the Miller Center for the study of the presidency, the election was noteworthy for occurring at all, an unprecedented democratic exercise in the midst of a civil war.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Republican dissidents who called themselves Radical Republicans formed a party named the Radical Democratic Party and nominated John C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont as their candidate for president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont later withdrew and endorsed Lincoln.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] War Democrats joined with Republicans as the National Union Party, with Lincoln at the head of the ticket.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The National Union Party was a temporary name used to attract War Democrats and Southern Border State Unionists who would not vote for the Republican Party.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It faced off against the regular Democratic Party, including Peace Democrats.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election conventions of the parties are considered below in order of the party's popular vote.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War progressed, political opinions within the Republican Party began to diverge.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Senators Charles Sumner and Henry Wilson from Massachusetts wanted the Republican Party to advocate constitutional amendments to prohibit slavery and guarantee racial equality before the law.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Initially, not all northern Republicans supported such measures.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic leaders hoped that the radical Republicans would put forth their own ticket in the election.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* newspaper, particularly interested in undermining the National Union Party, ran a series of articles predicting a delay for the National Union Convention until late in 1864 to allow Frémont time to collect delegates to win the nomination.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont supporters in New York City established a newspaper called the *New Nation*, which declared in one of its initial issues that the National Union Convention would be a "nonentity".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* also published false information (further purported by Samuel S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Before the election, some War Democrats joined the Republicans to form the National Union Party.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With the outcome of the Civil War still in doubt, some political leaders, including Salmon P.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase, Benjamin Wade, and Horace Greeley, opposed Lincoln's re-nomination on the grounds that he could not win.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase himself became the only candidate to contest Lincoln's re-nomination actively, but he withdrew in March when a slew of Republican officials, including some within the state of Ohio upon whom Chase's campaign depended, endorsed Lincoln for re-nomination.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was still popular with most members of the Republican Party, and the National Union Party nominated him for a second term as president at their convention in Baltimore, Maryland, on June 7–8, 1864.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent vice president Hannibal Hamlin remaining indifferent about the prospect of a second term in office, Andrew Johnson, the former senator from and current military governor of Tennessee, was named as Lincoln's vice presidential running-mate.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He had been governor of Tennessee from 1853 to 1857 and was elected by the legislature to the Senate in 1857.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his congressional service, he sought passage of the Homestead Bill which was enacted soon after he left his Senate seat in 1862.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] When the Southern slave states, including Tennessee, seceded, he remained firmly with the Union.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was the only sitting senator from a Confederate state who did not resign his seat upon learning of his state's secession.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1862, Lincoln appointed him as military governor of Tennessee after most of it had been retaken.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1864, Johnson was a logical choice as running mate for Lincoln, who wished to send a message of national unity in his re-election campaign, especially to ensure the electoral votes of the border states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Others who were considered for the nomination, at one point or another, were former Senator Daniel Dickinson, Major General Benjamin Butler, Major General William Rosecrans, Joseph Holt, and former Treasury Secretary and Senator John Dix.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party was bitterly split between War Democrats and Peace Democrats, a group further divided among competing factions.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Moderate Peace Democrats who supported the war against the Confederacy, such as Horatio Seymour, were preaching the wisdom of a negotiated peace.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After the Union victory at the Battle of Gettysburg in 1863, moderate Peace Democrats proposed a negotiated peace that would secure Union victory.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They believed this was the best course of action, because an armistice could finish the war without devastating the South.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Radical Peace Democrats known as Copperheads, such as Thomas H.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Seymour, declared the war to be a failure and favored an immediate end to hostilities without securing Union victory.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan vied for the presidential nomination.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, friends of Horatio Seymour insisted on placing his name before the convention, which was held in Chicago, Illinois, on August 29–31, 1864.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] But on the day before the organization of that body, Horatio Seymour announced positively that he would not be a candidate.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Since the Democrats were divided by issues of war and peace, they sought a strong candidate who could unify the party.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The compromise was to nominate pro-war General George B.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan for president and anti-war Representative George H.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, a War Democrat, was nominated for president over the Copperhead Thomas H.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Pendleton, a close associate of the Copperhead Clement Vallandigham, balanced the ticket, since he was known for having strongly opposed the Union war effort.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention adopted a peace platform – a platform McClellan personally rejected.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan supported the continuation of the war and restoration of the Union, but the party platform, written by Vallandigham, opposed this position.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Radical Democratic Convention assembled in Ohio with delegates arriving on May 29, 1864.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] *The New York Times* reported that the hall which the convention organizers had planned to use had been double-booked by an opera troupe.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Almost all delegates were instructed to support Frémont, with a major exception being the New York delegation, which was composed of War Democrats who supported Ulysses S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Various estimates of the number of delegates were reported in the press; *The New York Times* reported 156 delegates, but the number generally reported elsewhere was 350 delegates.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates came from 15 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They adopted the name Radical Democratic Party.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A supporter of Grant was appointed chairman.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The platform was passed with little discussion, and a series of resolutions that bogged down the convention proceedings were voted down decisively.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention nominated Frémont for president, and he accepted the nomination on June 4, 1864.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his letter, he stated that he would step aside if the National Union Convention would nominate someone other than Lincoln for president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] John Cochrane was nominated for vice president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 election was the first time since 1812 that a presidential election took place during a war.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For much of 1864, Lincoln himself believed he had little chance of being re-elected.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Confederate forces had triumphed at the Battle of Mansfield, the Battle of Cold Harbor, the Battle of Brices Cross Roads, the Battle of Kennesaw Mountain and the Battle of the Crater.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the war was continuing to take a very high toll in terms of casualties with campaigns such as Grant's Overland Campaign and the perceived lack of progress.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The prospect of a long and bloody war started to make the idea of "peace at all cost" offered by the Ultra Peace Democrats look more desirable.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] However, several political and military events eventually made Lincoln's re-election inevitable.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the first place, the Democrats had to confront the severe internal strains within their party at the Democratic National Convention.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The political compromises made at the Democratic National Convention were contradictory and made McClellan's efforts to campaign seem inconsistent.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Secondly, the Democratic National Convention influenced Frémont's campaign.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont was appalled at the Democratic platform, which he described as "union with slavery".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After three weeks of discussions with Cochrane and his supporters, Frémont withdrew from the race in September 1864.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his statement, Frémont declared that winning the Civil War was too important to divide the Republican vote.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Although he still felt that Lincoln was not going far enough, the defeat of McClellan was of the greatest necessity.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] General Cochrane, who was a War Democrat, agreed and withdrew with Frémont.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] On September 23, 1864, Frémont also brokered a political deal in which Lincoln removed U.S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Postmaster General Montgomery Blair from office, and on September 24 Abraham Lincoln relieved Blair of his duty as Postmaster General.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan's chances of victory faded after Frémont withdrew from the presidential race.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lastly, with the fall of Atlanta on September 2, there was no longer any question that a Union military victory was inevitable and close at hand.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, the Union Party mobilized the full strength of both the Republicans and the War Democrats under the slogan "Don't change horses in the middle of a stream".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It was energized as Lincoln made emancipation the central issue, and state Republican parties stressed the perfidy of the Copperheads.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] 24.4% of the voting age population and 76.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The American Civil War was in progress and unfinished during this election.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Because eleven Southern states plus two claimed additional Southern states had declared secession from the Union and formed the Confederate States of America, only twenty-five states participated in the election.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Louisiana and Tennessee had recently been re-captured.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They chose presidential electors, but their votes were rejected by Congress due to having recently seceded from the Union.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Both states had voted for Lincoln, so it would not have changed the result in any case.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Three new states participated for the first time: Kansas, West Virginia, and Nevada.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan won just three states: Kentucky, Delaware, and his home state of New Jersey.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln won in every state he carried in 1860 except New Jersey, and also carried a state won four years earlier by Stephen Douglas (Missouri), one carried by John C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge (Maryland) and all three newly admitted states (Kansas, Nevada and West Virginia).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Altogether, 212 electoral votes were counted in Congress for Lincoln – more than enough to win the presidency even if all of the states in rebellion had participated and voted against him.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This would be the last election in which a party nominee won completely different states than the previous nominee, with McClellan flipping Kentucky and New Jersey, while having lost Missouri.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was highly popular with soldiers and they in turn recommended him to their families back home.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The following states allowed soldiers to cast ballots: California, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine, Michigan, Rhode Island, and Wisconsin.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Only soldiers from Kentucky gave McClellan a majority of their votes, and he carried the army vote in the state by a vote of 2,823 (70.3%) to 1,194 (29.7%).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,129 counties making returns, Lincoln won in 728 (64.5%), while McClellan carried 400 (35.4%).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] One county (0.1%) in Iowa split evenly between Lincoln and McClellan.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election the Republicans won in Maryland until 1896.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] (a) *The states in rebellion did not participate in the election of 1864.* (b) *The 17 electoral votes from Tennessee and Louisiana were rejected.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1864-united-states-presidential-election] States in red were won by Republican Abraham Lincoln; states in blue were won by Democrat George B.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation was launched before the adjournment of the trial and continued after the trial adjourned on May 26, 1868.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The leading figure of the investigation was Benjamin Butler.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The final report of the investigation was published on July 3, 1868.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On February 21, 1868, in disregard for the Tenure of Office Act, Andrew Johnson (the president of the United States) attempted to replace Edwin Stanton (the United States secretary of war) with Lorenzo Thomas.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This led the United States House of Representatives, on February 24, to impeach Johnson.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After the impeachment, an impeachment trial began in the United States Senate where the Senate would judge whether to convict Johnson, thereby removing him from office.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] While the investigation never proved bribery, there is evidence of efforts by both those supporting the prosecution and the defense having made offers to senators to persuade their votes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This includes evidence of promises of patronage jobs, cash bribes, and political dealmaking being made to solicit votes for acquittal.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] There is evidence that the prosecution may have attempted to bribe the senators voting for acquittal to switch their votes to conviction.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Aspects of this possible scheme were partially uncovered by the investigation, but it was never proven by the investigation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] All of the individuals, except for Wooley, had ties to United States Secretary of State William H.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Seward, who also appears implicated in this scheme.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Evidence also suggests that Alexander Randall and Edmund Cooper (a leader at the United States Department of the Treasury) were possibly in charge of managing an "acquittal fund" for Johnson.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On May 16, 1868, the Senate voted against convicting Johnson on the eleventh article of impeachment, which had been considered the article with the strongest chance of securing a conviction.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It fell one vote shy of the two-thirds needed for impeachment, with the vote to convict being 32–21.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After this, the Senate voted to adjourn the trial and reconvene to resume voting on the remaining ten articles of impeachment on March 26, 1868.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This resolution had been justified by the impeachment managers with the claim that information had been provided to them that provided them with probable cause to suspect improper or corrupt means had influenced the Senate vote.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After the resolution passed, a subcommittee was created and began hearing testimony during the hiatus.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation that subsequently unfolded proved relatively extreme and unconstrained.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The leading force of the investigation was Benjamin Butler (R– MA).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers, during the hiatus between votes, began searching for possible corrupt means that may have persuaded senators to acquit.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation took a heavy-handed prosecutorial approach, subpoenaing telegrams, and looking into the bank accounts of private citizens that just-so happened to have withdrawn large amounts.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler was confident that votes had been bought by Johnson allies, and wanted to prove it.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The effort was disparaged as a "smelling committee" by Democrats and some of the press.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Many Republicans were also dubious towards the investigation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] While there is substantial evidence to suggest that there were several senators that voted to convict who Johnson could likely have counted on to vote for an acquittal had their votes been needed, only those who actually voted to convict were the focus of the impeachment managers' investigation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Among the telegrams found were a number that seemed incriminating.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Hours before the vote on May 16 to acquit, Charles Woolley sent Congressman George H.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Pendleton (D– OH) a telegram reading, "Andy all right." Many witnesses testified that they had heard talk of vote-purchasing, but many of these witnesses were also unable to recall who they heard it from or greater details about what they had heard.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Within hours of the authorization of the investigation, the impeachment managers had subpoenaed eight witnesses, including Senator Edmund G.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ross (who had voted to acquit), Perry Fuller (an Indian trader and a political fixer), and several individuals from Missouri that had tried unsuccessfully to convince John B.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] That evening, the committee began hearing testimony, with their first witness being Senator Ross' brother William, who expressed disappointment in his brother's vote but denied any knowledge of corruption in the Senate vote.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers received a large number of tips from people around the country of leads they should pursue.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] However, the individual who had Butler's ear the most with his advice on this was *National Police Gazette*-publisher George Wilkes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wilkes' newspaper was known to scandalmonger.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wilkes had a secret informant that was close to Samuel Ward (a notable lobbyist).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This source reported that Ward had paid Senator Edmund G.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ross for his vote to acquit with $12,000 from Democratic congressman John Morrissey.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wilkes speculated that the transfer of money was handled by "Charley Morgan", who was a cross-dresser who was allegedly involved in separate extramarital affairs with both Morrissey's wife and Samuel Ward.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] During the middle of the investigation, a young woman going by the name "Charley Morgan" was arrested in New York, pleading guilty to a misdemeanor charge of "indecency" for crossdressing.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] She told the court that she had gone four years without wearing women's clothing.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler, however, gave assurances to Ward that this was not his doing, pointing to the fact that he had gone against pressure to embarrass Ward by calling her as a witness in the investigation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler would never find proof that Ward had bribed Ross.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation included a focus on a number of Johnson-allied figures, including Thurlow Weed and Charles Woolley.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Thurlow Weed told the committee that there had been a group that was determined to secure Johnson's acquittal.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Smythe was an individual that had been accused of corruption in the past, and had previously nearly been ejected from office as a result.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Weed also said that it included Sheridan Shook, former congressman Samuel S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] During the investigation, there was evidence found that United States Secretary of State William Seward and Postmaster General Alexander Randall had been in contact with Cornelius Wendell (a Washington printer) for the purposes of organizing bribes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wendell told the committee that he had been uninterested in being part of this plan, and pointed blame on Seward's aide Erastus Webster, who it appeared had collected a fund of $165,000 for the purposes of buying acquittal votes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This money was said to have primarily been raised by Randall, Hugh McCulloch (United States secretary of the treasury) and Henry A.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Smythe through middlemen such as Perry Fuller and James Legate (a special agent of the Kansas Post Office Department), though Fuller and Legate were said to have pocketed most of the money raised for themselves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wendell also testified about Charles Woolley's alleged involvement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] James Legate testified that Perry Fuller had told him that, if impeachment failed, Salmon Chase (the chief Justice of the United States, who acted as the trial's presiding officer) would run a third-party campaign for the presidency.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He also said that the raising of money for a potential Chase presidential bid was being used as a front for establishing a fund to support the acquittal of Johnson.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Among the other individuals interviewed was Thomas Ewing Jr.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Much evidence implicated Senator Samuel C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Pomeroy, who had voted to convict, in possible corruption.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler attempted to ignore this evidence, however.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation uncovered evidence that there had been discussions of bribes for votes to convict.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was discovered during the investigation that Kansas Senator Pomeroy, who voted for conviction, had written a letter to Johnson's postmaster general seeking a $40,000 bribe for Pomeroy's acquittal vote along with three or four others in his caucus.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Woolley became a central focus of Butler's from the first day of the trial.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers sought to hear from Woolley, who kept giving changing excuses for inability to come before them.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Among the matters they had questions for Woolley about was $10,000 that he had received from Sheridan Shook, a deputy collector of internal revenue in New York.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Woolley had withdrawn the money in $1,000 bills, which drew suspicion.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] When he appeared himself, Shook answered very few questions in his testimony before the committee, and many of his answers were seen as nonsensical.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Other witnesses on this matter had feigned ignorance or had been otherwise evasive in their answers to questions.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ordway (the sergeant at arms of the House) took custody of Woolley and brought him before the House on March 26.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] However, Woolley's appearance was interrupted that day by a recess so that congressmen could attend the Senate impeachment trial vote that day.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The committee submitted a report on their preliminary findings on May 26, hours before the Senate met again to vote on articles of impeachment.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] While some senators attempted to get the trial to adjourn until the end of June to allow the impeachment managers more time to investigate before the vote.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This was rejected because few others believed that the allegations could be proven.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The Senate voted identically on the second and third articles of impeachment, again by 32–21 votes before voting to adjourn sine die.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On March 26, 1868, after the trial adjourned, the House voted 91–30 to approve a resolution presented by Benjamin Butler authorizing the House impeachment managers to continue this investigation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler led the continuation of the investigation and conducted hearings and inquiry into widespread reports that Republican senators had been bribed to vote for Johnson's acquittal.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On March 26, shortly after the Senate trial adjourned, the impeachment managers returned to question Charles Woolley.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He failed to cooperate with their questioning, refusing to answer questions that he asserted were unrelated to the trial.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This included questions about what he had done with $10,000 that he had received from a deputy collector of internal revenue in New York named Sheridan Shook.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After this, House voted 60–51 that day to hold him in contempt of Congress and had him held in custody by the sergeant at arms of the House.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He was first kept in the House Committee on Foreign Affairs' hearing room, but, as his arrest grew in length, he was later moved to the basement room that Vinnie Ream had been utilizing as a sculpture studio, forcing the artist to move her work into the hallway.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Conservatives charged that Benjamin Butler was intentionally targeting Ream in his successful resolution to turn her studio into a Capitol Police guardroom.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Woolley's arrest attracted great media attention.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] When Woolley was questioned on May 27, he was denied a request for a lawyer.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler found him still inadequately responsive to questions, and sent him back to his holding cell.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The final report Butler wrote doubted this, calling it a, "stupid fabrication".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Eleven days later, Woolley told that house he would answer Butler's questions, and Butler questioned him again.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Van Valkenberg came before the committee again, with $17,000 of cash and accompanied by a hotel manager who told the impeachment managers that this money had indeed been in a hotel safe.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was impossible to prove whether this was Woolley's money or not.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After he appeared before the investigative committee and answered their questions to an extent that they found satisfactory, the House voted to discharge Woolley from their custody on June 11, 1868.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers took testimony for a total of six weeks the May 16 authorization of their investigation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In some instances, Butler individually interrogated witnesses.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] During these six weeks, Butler had detectives search for proof of bribery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] There was some speculation that Butler was motivated by a desire to not be blamed himself for the failure to secure a conviction.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was rumored, however, that Butler hidden thirty-six volumes of incriminating telegrams in hopes he could later use them to blackmail congressional colleagues in the future.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was also rumored that Butler had offered $100,000 to Cornelius Wendell in exchange for information, but had suppressed evidence of this offer.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In the post-trial hearings and investigations there was growing evidence that some acquittal votes were acquired by promises of patronage jobs and cash bribes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Grimes received assurances that acquittal would not be followed by presidential reprisals; Johnson agreed to enforce the Reconstruction Acts, and to appoint General John Schofield to succeed Stanton.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Nonetheless, the investigations never resulted in charges, much less convictions, against anyone.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation also boomeranged by uncovering evidence that there had been discussions of bribes for vote to covict.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Democrats were not worried by the investigation, and came to see it as amusing due to Butler's failure to find hard evidence of bribery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was reported that the impeachment managers had testimony showing implications of bribery, but did not provide solid evidence of bribery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In contrast the strictness that Woolley had faced, the impeachment managers were more lax when it came to the testimony of some witnesses.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] A number of witnesses were allowed to decline to answer questions, be evasive, or contradict evidence without consequence.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Some witnesses faced informal questioning that was not under oath.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Samuel Ward smoked cigars with Butler after he testified before the committee for two hours.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Adams, being questioned for allegedly originating a bribery scheme, gave what the impeachment managers found to be an "utterly false and untruthful" claim by declaring he could not recall at what time he had become a general, Butler did not pursue any action against him.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler, perhaps, was selective with what truths he sought to uncover in the investigation, hoping only to find those that would harm the president and the Democratic Party and help the Republicans.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Even when it came to matters he wanted to uncover, Butler appears to have been selective in which leads he chose to follow, disregarding some leads more that were potentially promising than the ones he chose to follow.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Fowler as having been bribed for his vote against impeachment.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Seven congressmen gave a statement that, in January 1868, Fowler had demanded the impeachment of Johnson.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Henderson, who had promised to vote to convict on the eleventh article four days before he voted to acquit on it.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] There is historical evidence that Perry Fuller had bribed Senator Ross.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] However, Butler never managed to prove this act of bribery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Fuller admitted that, at the authority of Edmund Cooper, he had offered $40,000 to Senator Samuel C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Pomeroy's brother-in-law Willis Gaylord.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In late-May 1868, amid the investigation, he acknowledged having paid for the outstanding expense of the home mortgage of James Legate.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It appears that Legate had also given Fuller his records of the bribery scheme, and that Fuller had burned them.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Historical evidence shows that Fuller had admitted to doing so in hopes of, "drying up the investigation".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Being unable to definitively prove that bribery took place, Butler wrote a final report on the evidence found and testimony taken by the impeachment managers in their investigation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler rushedly published the final report of the investigation on July 3, 1868.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He hoped that this would hurt Johnson's prospects at the Democratic Party's presidential nomination at the 1868 Democratic National Convention held in New York City the following week.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Senators suspected of selling their acquittal votes attacked the report on the Senate floor.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ross attacked what he called Butler's, "well-known groveling instincts and proness to slime and uncleanness".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Eighteen months after the end of the trial, journalist Henry V.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Boynton published an investigative news report that sought to tie up loose ends in Butler's investigation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He identified three different alleged bribery schemes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Boynton was unhappy with Butler's handling of the impeachment managers' investigation, believing his pursuit of Woolley had been to the detriment of pursuing other guilty parties.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He was also angered by Butler's failure to publish important testimony from the investigation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Cornelius Wendell gave a news interview that confirmed aspects of Boynton's reporting, and which accused Perry Fuller of offering Senator Ross several thousand dollars to influence his vote.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Few transcripts of testimony from the investigation survive.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The **1913 Gettysburg reunion** was a Gettysburg Battlefield encampment of American Civil War veterans for the Battle of Gettysburg's 50th anniversary.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The June 29 – July 4 gathering of 53,407 veterans (about 8,750 Confederate) was the largest Civil War veteran reunion.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] All honorably-discharged veterans in the Grand Army of the Republic and the United Confederate Veterans were invited, and veterans from 46 of the 48 states attended (all except Nevada and Wyoming).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Despite official concerns "that there might be unpleasant differences, at least, between the blue and gray" (as after England's War of the Roses and the French Revolution), the peaceful reunion was characterized by instances of Union–Confederate camaraderie.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] After a number of smaller Gettysburg reunions, including the 1906 Philadelphia Brigade-Pickett's Division reunion during which Brigadier General Lewis Armistead's captured sword was returned to the South, in April 1908 General Henry S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Huidekoper of Philadelphia suggested a 1913 50th anniversary reunion to Pennsylvania Governor Edwin Sydney Stuart.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On September 8, the Gettysburg National Park Commission met with Gettysburg borough officials about the event.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Stuart held a sub-committee meeting on October 25, and addressed the General Assembly about the matter in January 1909.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On May 13, 1909, the Pennsylvania Assembly created the Fiftieth Anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg Commission.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The commission's "first tentative programme" of October 13, 1910 included a "Peace Jubilee", with a noon July 3 placement of the cornerstone for a "Great Peace Memorial".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The August 26, 1912, US Congress bill appropriated $150,000 and directed the War Department to establish the camp.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Because the memorial funding was not approved, the Peace Jubilee plans were removed from the schedule.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The site of the camp and the 8 acres (3.2 ha) for the Great Tent, west of the Codori House, were selected in 1912 and mapped by the Gettysburg National Park Commission.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The commission also painted avenue fencing, gun carriages, iron tablets, pyramids, and shells from 1912 through June 30, 1913.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On April 13, 1913, the Pennsylvania commission completed the Pennsylvania State Memorial and mailed invitations to 40,000 veterans.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On June 28, President Woodrow Wilson notified the Pennsylvania commission that he would attend the reunion for a "very limited period".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The 33 contributing states provided a total of $1,033,000 for the reunion, with $450,000 coming from Pennsylvania.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania commission headquarters at Gettysburg was at 231 Baltimore Street, with the Harrisburg office of the Secretary (later nicknamed the "Duke of Gettysburg") in Pennsylvania State Capitol's Room 509.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Commemorative tokens and programs were designed for attendees, including three types of Pennsylvania badges ("Press", "Guest", and "Scout"), a commemorative medal, and a souvenir program of poems by attending "Veteran Scout" Jack Crawford.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania Railroad added "a telephone line between Gettysburg and Hanover along the Western Maryland Railway, over which the Pennsy [would] operate a large number of trains during the battle anniversary".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On the Chambersburg-Gettysburg turnpike and the Gettysburg-Petersburg turnpike, tolls ended for the reunion.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania Supreme Court upheld the 1911 Sproul Roads Act on June 27, enabling the Commonwealth to acquire private toll roads and make them free for the public.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Water wells were being drilled for the July encampment by February 1, 1913, and hotels in Hanover, Chambersburg, Hagerstown, and "the Blue Ridge section [were] filling rapidly" by June 26.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The War Department's Great Camp (Gettysburg Encampment, Anniversary Camp, or Veterans Camp) provided tents and support facilities for the Civil War veterans and extended from both sides of Long Lane on the north to within 500 yd (460 m) of the Bliss House.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Post Office; 90 Pennsylvania Health Department latrines throughout the camp, with a seating capacity of 3,476; and (near the Great Tent) an emergency station and two health-department Comfort Houses which supplied the Great Tent water fountains.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania commission set up a temporary morgue in the camp.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A special platform on the Round Top Branch was built for veterans to disembark from steam trains into the camp; in February, trolleys of the Gettysburg Electric Railway had been prohibited from using the branch.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The department set up a field hospital on the Kurtz property facing Brickyard Lane on the north foot of East Cemetery Hill and six comfort stations in the borough: one at each railroad station.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The department tested borough wells and mitigated contamination sources upstream from the water-works supply on Marsh Creek.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The American Red Cross Society and 72 additional Boy Scouts operated fourteen 7 ft × 7 ft (2.1 m × 2.1 m) relief stations for first aid and rest on the battlefield-park roads.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Gettysburg's Tuberculosis Dispensary was also used as a relief station.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Attached to the Great Camp were a battery of the Third United States Field Artillery and several companies of regular infantry.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Companies A-D (14 officers and 285 men) of the Fifteenth United States Cavalry arrived on June 26 to guard the battlefield, camping west of Seminary Ridge on the Hagerstown Road.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A "model Camp" for a Pennsylvania cavalry squadron was on the "College Athletic Field" adjoining the commission's headquarters.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A total of 527 people were quartered at the Lutheran Theological Seminary at Gettysburg and Pennsylvania College (renamed Gettysburg College in 1921), including the Pennsylvania Gettysburg Commission, four troops of the Pennsylvania State Police, and (in tents) Governor Tener's staff.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The commission planned a four-day series of events, with each day dedicated to a different group.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Anticipating that some veterans might arrive early (especially those traveling a long distance), the Great Camp was opened for supper on June 29.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Pennsylvania veterans who attended the state reunion, which adjourned on June 28, made up most of the over 21,000 arrivals that day.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Other veterans arriving early included two Confederate veterans of Culp's Hill, who arrived on June 26.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Captain McCaskey of the Quartermasters Corps had estimated that 6,000 men might arrive on June 29, and temporarily struggled with shortages of food and supplies.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Some veterans left without staying another night.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On June 30, the 1912 base of the Virginia Monument was dedicated; the rest of the monument was completed later.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] At night, a "Union raid" on the Confederate side of the Great Camp was followed by joint parades and campfires.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] ; eight senators, and 21 congressmen were among the officials who arrived that day.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] at 9 p.m. included "gigantic set pieces covering the entire face and crest of Little Round Top".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] ; eight statues had been installed in April.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Woodrow Wilson arrived at 11 a.m. in a special rail car, traveled through the borough, and entered the Great Tent through two rows of Boy Scouts.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] He addressed the audience in the Big Tent about national unity, and left the camp after the National Anthem was played.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] At noon, a five-minute tribute was held in silence for "Our Heroic Dead"; people throughout the area stood at attention, including at the "College Hotel" and "Seminary Hotel".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The tribute began with a bugle salute while the Gettysburg bells in the distance tolled.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The remaining minutes of silence were punctuated by periodic artillery firing in the distance.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] From 5 a.m. to 11 p.m., 7,147 automobiles used the national-park roads as visitors departed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] About 12,000 veterans had already left on July 2, and about the same number on July 3.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] During the evening of July 2 at the Hotel Gettysburg.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Henry (a Southerner living in Philadelphia) uttered a "vile epithet" about President Abraham Lincoln and caused an argument at his table.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A Union man threw his drink at Henry, who stabbed and slashed men at the table and on his way out to the street before he was apprehended.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Virginia governor spoke to officials on behalf of Henry, and his father (a Confederate major) posted bail for his son.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The victims (all but one of whom were taken to a hospital) were all expected to recover, and most were released from the hospital the next day.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Dismantling of the Great Camp began immediately after the July 4 tribute.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The hospital closed on July 5, and the last veteran left on July 8.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The annual military instructional camp (250 college students) used several tents in the veterans' camp at the "Meadeboro" camp (Newspaper Row) from July 7 to August 15.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The quartermaster headquarters on Baltimore Street closed on August 13, and by August 15 the Grand Camp had been removed except for "four great water storage reservoirs".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A film, *United at Gettysburg*, documented the reunion and was shown at local theaters.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Beitler, Secretary of the Commission, finished compiling the organizations' reports on December 31, 1913.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/1913-gettysburg-reunion] To commemorate the reunion, a colonial portico was opened in May 1914 at the seminary's Old Dorm; only the concrete base remains.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery movement originated during the Age of Enlightenment, focused on ending the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In Colonial America, a few German Quakers issued the 1688 Germantown Quaker Petition Against Slavery, which marked the beginning of the American abolitionist movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the Revolutionary War, evangelical colonists were the primary advocates for the opposition to slavery and the slave trade, doing so on the basis of humanitarian ethics.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, others such as James Oglethorpe, the founder of the colony of Georgia, also retained political motivations for the removal of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Prohibiting slavery through the 1735 Georgia Experiment in part to prevent Spanish partnership with Georgia's runaway slaves, Oglethorpe eventually revoked the act in 1750 after the Spanish's defeat in the Battle of Bloody Marsh eight years prior.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] During the Revolutionary era, all states abolished the international slave trade, but South Carolina reversed its decision.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between the Revolutionary War and 1804, laws, constitutions, or court decisions in each of the Northern states provided for the gradual or immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No Southern state adopted similar policies.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1807, Congress made the importation of slaves a crime, effective January 1, 1808, which was as soon as Article I, section 9 of the Constitution allowed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A small but dedicated group, under leaders such as William Lloyd Garrison and Frederick Douglass, agitated for abolition in the mid-19th century.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown became an advocate and militia leader in attempting to end slavery by force of arms.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Civil War, immediate emancipation became a war goal for the Union in 1863 and was fully achieved in 1865.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism began well before the United States was founded as a nation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1652, Rhode Island made it illegal for any person, black or white, to be "bound" longer than ten years.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The law, however, was widely ignored, and Rhode Island became involved in the slave trade in 1700.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] An early prominent example of resistance by enslaved people occurred during Bacon's Rebellion in 1676.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Occurring in Virginia, the rebellion saw European indentured servants and African people (of indentured, enslaved, and free negroes) band together against William Berkeley because of his refusal to fully remove Native American tribes in the region.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the time, Native Americans in the region were hosting raids against lower-class settlers encroaching on their land after the Third Powhatan War (1644–1646), which left many white and black indentured servants and slaves without a sense of protection from their government.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Led by Nathaniel Bacon, the unification that occurred between the white lower class and blacks during this rebellion was perceived as dangerous and thus was quashed with the implementation of the Virginia Slave Codes of 1705.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, this event introduced the premise that blacks and whites could work together towards the goal of self-liberation, which became increasingly prevalent as abolition gained traction within America.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first written statement against slavery in Colonial America was prepared in 1688 by members of the Religious Society of Friends.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The intention of the petition was to stop slavery within the Quaker community, where 70% of Quakers owned slaves between 1681 and 1705.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It acknowledged the universal rights of all people.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the Quaker establishment did not take action at that time, the unusually early, clear, and forceful argument in the petition initiated the spirit that finally led to the end of slavery in the Society of Friends (1776) and in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania (1780).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Quaker Quarterly Meeting of Chester, Pennsylvania, made its first protest in 1711.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Within a few decades the entire slave trade was under attack, being opposed by such Quaker leaders as William Burling, Benjamin Lay, Ralph Sandiford, William Southby, John Woolman, and Anthony Benezet.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benezet was particularly influential, inspiring a later generation of notable anti-slavery activists, including Granville Sharp, John Wesley, Thomas Clarkson, Olaudah Equiano, Benjamin Franklin, Benjamin Rush, Absalom Jones, and Bishop Richard Allen, among others.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Samuel Sewall, a prominent Bostonian, wrote *The Selling of Joseph* (1700) in protest of the widening practice of outright slavery as opposed to indentured servitude in the colonies.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This is the earliest-recorded anti-slavery tract published in the future United States.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery was banned in the colony of Georgia soon after its founding in 1733.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The colony's founder, James Edward Oglethorpe, fended off repeated attempts by South Carolina merchants and land speculators to introduce slavery into the colony.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His motivations included tactical defense against Spanish collusion with runaway slaves, and prevention of Georgia's largely reformed criminal population from replicating South Carolina's planter class structure.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1737, Quaker abolitionist Benjamin Lay published *All Slave-Keepers That Keep the Innocent in Bondage, Apostates*, which was printed by his friend, Benjamin Franklin.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The event resulted in 25 colonists and 35 to 50 African slaves killed, as well as the implementation of the 1740 Negro Act to prevent another slave uprising.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In her book, "The Slave's Cause" by Manisha Sinha, Sinha considers the Stono Rebellion to be an important act of abolition from the perspective of the slave, recognizing their agency and subsequent humanity as cause for self-liberation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The struggle between Georgia and South Carolina led to the first debates in Parliament over the issue of slavery, occurring between 1740 and 1742.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Rhode Island Quakers, associated with Moses Brown, were among the first in America to free slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benjamin Rush was another leader, as were many Quakers.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Woolman gave up most of his business in 1756 to devote himself to campaigning against slavery along with other Quakers.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between 1764 and 1774, seventeen enslaved African Americans appeared before the Massachusetts courts in freedom suits, spurred on the decision made in the *Somerset v.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Stewart* case, which although not applying the colonies was still received positively by American abolitionists.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Boston lawyer Benjamin Kent represented them.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whipple*) to liberate Jenny Slew, a mixed-race woman who had been kidnapped in Massachusetts and then handled as a slave.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian Steven Pincus, many of the colonial legislatures worked to enact laws that would limit slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Provincial legislature of Massachusetts Bay, as noted by historian Gary B.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nash, approved a law "prohibiting the importation and purchase of slaves by any Massachusetts citizen." The Loyalist governor of Massachusetts, Thomas Hutchinson, vetoed the law, an action that prompted angered reaction from the general public.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionists were cheered by the decision in *Somerset v Stewart* (1772), which prohibited slavery in the United Kingdom, though not in its colonies.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1774, the influential Fairfax Resolves called for an end to the "wicked, cruel and unnatural" Atlantic slave trade.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One of the first articles advocating the emancipation of slaves and the abolition of slavery was written by Thomas Paine.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Titled "African Slavery in America", it appeared on 8 March 1775 in the *Postscript to the Pennsylvania Journal and Weekly Advertiser*.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Society for the Relief of Free Negroes Unlawfully Held in Bondage (Pennsylvania Abolition Society) was the first American abolition society, formed 14 April 1775, in Philadelphia, primarily by Quakers.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The society suspended operations during the American Revolutionary War and was reorganized in 1784, with Benjamin Franklin as its first president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1777, the Vermont Republic became the first independent state in North America to prohibit slavery: slaves were not directly freed, but masters were required to remove slaves from Vermont.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Constitution included several provisions which accommodated slavery, although none used the word.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Passed unanimously by the Congress of the Confederation in 1787, the Northwest Ordinance forbade slavery in the Northwest Territory, a vast area (the future Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, and Wisconsin) in which slavery had been legal, but population was sparse.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to begin a gradual abolition of slavery was Pennsylvania, in 1780.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All importation of slaves was prohibited, but none were freed at first, only the slaves of masters who failed to register them with the state, along with the "future children" of enslaved mothers.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Those enslaved in Pennsylvania before the 1780 law went into effect were not freed until 1847.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Massachusetts took a much more radical position.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1780, during the Revolution, Massachusetts ratified its constitution and included within it a clause that declared all men equal.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Based upon this clause, several freedom suits were filed by enslaved African Americans living in Massachusetts.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1783, its Supreme Court, in the case of *Commonwealth v.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nathaniel Jennison*, reaffirmed the case of *Brom and Bett v.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Ashley*, which held that even slaves were people who had a constitutional right to liberty.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This gave freedom to slaves, effectively abolishing slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] States with a greater economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, passed gradual emancipation laws.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While some of these laws were gradual, these states enacted the first abolition laws in the entire "New World".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the State of New York, the enslaved population was transformed into indentured servants before being granted full emancipation in 1827.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In other states, abolitionist legislation provided freedom only for the children of the enslaved.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In New Jersey, slavery was not fully prohibited until the passage of the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All of the other states north of Maryland began gradual abolition of slavery between 1781 and 1804, based on the Pennsylvania model and by 1804, all the Northern states had passed laws to gradually or immediately abolish it.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slaves continued in involuntary, unpaid "indentured servitude" for two more decades, and others were moved south and sold to new owners in slave states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some individual slaveholders, particularly in the upper South, freed slaves, sometimes in their wills.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many noted they had been moved by the revolutionary ideals of the equality of men.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The number of free blacks as a proportion of the black population in the upper South increased from less than 1 percent to nearly 10 percent between 1790 and 1810 as a result of these actions.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slave owners, concerned about the increase in free blacks, which they viewed as destabilizing, freed slaves on condition that they emigrate to Africa.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All U.S. states abolished the transatlantic slave trade by 1798.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] South Carolina, which had abolished the slave trade in 1787, reversed that decision in 1803.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the American South, freedom suits were rejected by the courts, which held that the rights in the state constitutions did not apply to African Americans.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The institution of slavery remained solid in the South, and that region's customs and social beliefs evolved into a strident defense of slavery in response to the rise of a growing anti-slavery stance in the North.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1835 alone, abolitionists mailed over a million pieces of anti-slavery literature to the South, giving rise to the gag rules in Congress, after the theft of mail from the Charleston, South Carolina, post office, and much back-and-forth about whether postmasters were required to deliver this mail.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Postmaster General, they were not.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under the Constitution, the importation of enslaved persons could not be prohibited until 1808 (20 years).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As the end of the 20 years approached, an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves sailed through Congress with little opposition.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] President Jefferson signed it, and it went effect on January 1, 1808.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1820, the Act to Protect the Commerce of the United States and Punish the Crime of Piracy was passed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This law made importing slaves into the United States a death penalty offense.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1830, most Americans were, at least in principle, opposed to slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, opponents of slavery deliberated on how to end the institution, as well as what would become of the slaves once they were free.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1830s there was a progressive shift in thinking in the North.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Mainstream opinion changed from gradual emancipation and resettlement of freed blacks in Africa, sometimes a condition of their manumission, to immediatism: freeing all the slaves immediately and sorting out the problems later.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This change was in many cases sudden, a consequence of the individual's coming in direct contact with the horrors of American slavery, or hearing of them from a credible source.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American beginning of abolitionism as a political movement is usually dated from 1 January 1831, when Wm.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison (as he always signed himself) published the first issue of his new weekly newspaper, *The Liberator* (1831), which appeared without interruption until slavery in the United States was abolished in 1865, when it closed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists included those who joined the American Anti-Slavery Society or its auxiliary groups in the 1830s and 1840s, as the movement fragmented.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The fragmented anti-slavery movement included groups such as the Liberty Party; the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society; the American Missionary Association; and the Church Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Historians traditionally distinguish between moderate anti-slavery reformers or gradualists, who concentrated on stopping the spread of slavery, and radical abolitionists or immediatists, whose demands for unconditional emancipation often merged with a concern for Black civil rights.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nearly all Northern politicians, such as Abraham Lincoln, rejected the "immediate emancipation" called for by the abolitionists, seeing it as "extreme".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, many Northern leaders, including Lincoln, Stephen Douglas (the Democratic nominee in 1860), John C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont (the Republican nominee in 1856), and Ulysses S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Grant married into slave-owning Southern families without any moral qualms.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Anti-slavery as a principle was far more than just the wish to prevent the expansion of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1840, abolitionists rejected this because it let sin continue to exist; they demanded that slavery end everywhere, immediately and completely.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown was the only abolitionist to have actually planned a violent insurrection, though David Walker promoted the idea.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement was strengthened by the activities of free African Americans, especially in the Black church, who argued that the old Biblical justifications for slavery contradicted the New Testament.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] African-American activists and their writings were rarely heard outside the Black community.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, they were tremendously influential on a few sympathetic white people, most prominently the first white activist to reach prominence, Wm.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison, who was its most effective propagandist.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Garrison's efforts to recruit eloquent spokesmen led to the discovery of ex-slave Frederick Douglass, who eventually became a prominent activist in his own right.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually, Douglass would publish his own widely distributed abolitionist newspaper, *North Star*.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1850s, the American abolitionist movement split into two camps over the question of whether the United States Constitution did or did not protect slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This issue arose in the late 1840s after the publication of *The Unconstitutionality of Slavery* by Lysander Spooner.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians, led by Garrison and Wendell Phillips, publicly burned copies of the Constitution, called it a pact with slavery, and demanded its abolition and replacement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another camp, led by Lysander Spooner, Gerrit Smith, and eventually Douglass, considered the Constitution to be an anti-slavery document.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Using an argument based upon Natural Law and a form of social contract theory, they said that slavery fell outside the Constitution's scope of legitimate authority and therefore should be abolished.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another split in the abolitionist movement was along class lines.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The artisan republicanism of Robert Dale Owen and Frances Wright stood in stark contrast to the politics of prominent elite abolitionists such as industrialist Arthur Tappan and his evangelist brother Lewis.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the former pair opposed slavery on a basis of solidarity of "wage slaves" with "chattel slaves", the Whiggish Tappans strongly rejected this view, opposing the characterization of Northern workers as "slaves" in any sense.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many American abolitionists took an active role in opposing slavery by supporting the Underground Railroad.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was made illegal by the federal Fugitive Slave Law of 1850, arguably the most hated and most openly evaded federal legislation in the nation's history.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nevertheless, participants like Harriet Tubman, Henry Highland Garnet, Alexander Crummell, Amos Noë Freeman, and others continued with their work.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were particularly active in Ohio, where some worked directly in the Underground Railroad.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Since only the Ohio River separated free Ohio from slave Kentucky, it was a popular destination for fugitive slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Supporters helped them there, in many cases to cross Lake Erie by boat, into Canada.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Western Reserve area of northeast Ohio was "probably the most intensely antislavery section of the country." The Oberlin-Wellington Rescue got national publicity.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionist John Brown grew up in Hudson, Ohio.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the South, members of the abolitionist movement or other people opposing slavery were often targets of lynch mob violence before the American Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His fellow Duffield Street residents Thomas and Harriet Truesdell were leading members of the abolitionist movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Truesdell was a founding member of the Providence Anti-slavery Society before moving to Brooklyn in 1838.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Harriet Truesdell was also very active in the movement, organizing an anti-slavery convention in Pennsylvania Hall (Philadelphia).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another prominent Brooklyn-based abolitionist was Rev.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Joshua Leavitt, trained as a lawyer at Yale, who stopped practicing law in order to attend Yale Divinity School, and subsequently edited the abolitionist newspaper *The Emancipator* and campaigned against slavery, as well as advocating other social reforms.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1841, Leavitt published *The Financial Power of Slavery*, which argued that the South was draining the national economy due to its reliance on enslaved workers.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2007, Duffield Street was given the name Abolitionist Place, and the Truesdells' home at 227 Duffield received landmark status in 2021.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was a direct result of the Union victory in the American Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The central issue of the war was slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the North, most opponents of slavery supported other modernizing reform movements such as the temperance movement, public schooling, and prison- and asylum-building.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They were split on the issue of women's activism and their political role, and this contributed to a major rift in the Society.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1839, brothers Arthur Tappan and Lewis Tappan left the Society and formed the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society, which did not admit women.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Other members of the Society, including Charles Turner Torrey, Amos Phelps, Henry Stanton, and Alanson St.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Clair, in addition to disagreeing with Garrison on the women's issue, urged taking a much more activist approach to abolitionism and consequently challenged Garrison's leadership at the Society's annual meeting in January 1839.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When the challenge was beaten back, they left and founded the New Organization, which adopted a more activist approach to freeing slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Soon after, in 1840, they formed the Liberty Party, which had as its sole platform the abolition of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1840, Garrison himself announced the formation of a third new organization, the Friends of Universal Reform, with sponsors and founding members including prominent reformers Maria Chapman, Abby Kelley Foster, Oliver Johnson, and Bronson Alcott (father of Louisa May Alcott).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists such as William Lloyd Garrison repeatedly condemned slavery for contradicting the principles of freedom and equality on which the country was founded.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most influential abolitionist publication was *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), the best-selling novel by Harriet Beecher Stowe, who had attended the anti-slavery debates at Lane, of which her father, Lyman Beecher, was the president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outraged by the Fugitive Slave Law of 1850 (which made the escape narrative part of everyday news), Stowe emphasized the horrors that abolitionists had long claimed about slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Her depiction of the evil slave owner Simon Legree, a transplanted Yankee who kills the Christ-like Uncle Tom, outraged the North, helped sway British public opinion against the South, and inflamed Southern slave owners who tried to refute it by showing that some slave owners were humanitarian.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It inspired numerous anti-Tom, pro-slavery novels, several written and published by women.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to a book reviewer, "Next to *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), Hinton Helper's critique of slavery and the Southern class system, *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857), was arguably the most important antislavery book of the 1850s." According to historian George M.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Two diametrically opposed anti-slavery positions emerged regarding the United States Constitution.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians emphasized that the document permitted and protected slavery and was therefore "an agreement with hell" that had to be rejected in favor of immediate emancipation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The mainstream anti-slavery position adopted by the new Republican party argued that the Constitution could and should be used to eventually end slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They assumed that the Constitution gave the government no authority to abolish slavery directly.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, there were multiple tactics available to support the long-term strategy of using the Constitution as a battering ram against the peculiar institution.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] First Congress could block the admission of any new slave states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] That would steadily move the balance of power in Congress and the Electoral College in favor of freedom.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could abolish slavery in the District of Columbia and the territories.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could use the Commerce Clause to end the interstate slave trade, thereby crippling the steady movement of slavery from the southeast to the southwest.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could recognize free blacks as full citizens and insist on due process rights to protect fugitive slaves from being captured and returned to bondage.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Finally, the government could use patronage powers to promote the anti-slavery cause across the country, especially in the border states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Pro-slavery elements considered the Republican strategy to be much more dangerous to their cause than radical abolitionism.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln's election was met by secession.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, the Republican strategy mapped the "crooked path to abolition" that prevailed during the Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1850s, the slave trade remained legal in all 16 states of the American South.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While slavery was fading away in the cities and border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cash crops such as cotton, sugar, rice, tobacco or hemp.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism, after Nat Turner's revolt ended its discussion in the South, was based in the North, and white Southerners alleged it fostered slave rebellion.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison, founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society, and writers such as John Greenleaf Whittier and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass, and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped to found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners for using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 attempted to resolve issues surrounding slavery caused by the War with Mexico and the admission to the Union of the slave Republic of Texas.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 was proposed by "The Great Compromiser" Henry Clay; support was coordinated by Senator Stephen A.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Law was a concession to the South.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were outraged, because the new law required Northerners to help in the capture and return of runaway slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1854, Congress passed the Kansas–Nebraska Act, which opened those territories to slavery if the local residents voted that way.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery gains made in previous compromises were reversed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A firestorm of outrage brought together former Whigs, Know-Nothings, and former Free Soil Democrats to form a new party in 1854–56, the Republican Party.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It included a program of rapid modernization involving the government promotion of industry, railroads, banks, free homesteads, and colleges, all to the annoyance of the South.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party denounced the Slave Power – that is the political power of the slave owners who supposedly controlled the national government for their own benefit and to the disadvantage of the ordinary white man.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republicans wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because its members believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southern leaders said the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the West made them second-class citizens, and challenged their autonomy.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and slavery decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the firing on Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When Lincoln called for troops to suppress the rebellion, four more slave states seceded.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The crisis in Kansas Territory and the neighboring slave state of Missouri turned bloody during what was known as the Bleeding Kansas crisis of the 1850s.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Proslavery *border ruffians* and *Bushwhackers* fought antislavery "free-staters" and *Jayhawkers*.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Paramilitary guerrilla warfare became widespread in the area, as a prelude to the Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The violence would spread to many other places, including the Senate Chamber of the U.S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Capitol where a Southern Democrat attacked a Northern Republican with a cane as his political allies watched.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Explorer, army veteran, and abolitionist John C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont ran as the first Republican nominee for president in 1856.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party crusaded on the slogan: "Free soil, free silver, free men, Frémont and victory!" Although he lost, the party showed a strong base.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It dominated in Yankee areas of New England, New York and the northern Midwest, and had a strong presence in the rest of the North.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It had almost no support in the South, where it was roundly denounced in 1856–60 as a divisive force that threatened civil war.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The newly-formed Republican Party gained quite a standing in the 1856 to 1857 election cycle in the U.S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] House and Senate, cementing its status as the primary party for abolitionists and northerners for some time.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Without using the term "containment", the new Party in the mid-1850s proposed a system of containing slavery once it gained control of the national government.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Militant abolitionists demanded *immediate* emancipation, not a slow-acting containment.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some rejected the new party, and in turn its leaders reassured voters they were not trying to abolish slavery in the U.S. altogether, which was politically impossible, and were just working against its spread.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown has been called "the most controversial of all 19th-century Americans".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whereas Garrison was a pacifist, Brown believed violence was unfortunately necessary to end slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The raid, though unsuccessful in the short term, may have helped Lincoln get elected and moved the Southern states to secede, leading to the Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians regard Brown as a crazed lunatic, while David S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Reynolds hails him as the man who "killed slavery, sparked the civil war, and seeded civil rights".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His raid in October 1859 involved a band of 22 men who seized the Federal armory at Harper's Ferry, Virginia (since 1863, West Virginia), knowing it contained tens of thousands of weapons.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown believed the South was on the verge of a gigantic slave uprising and that one spark would set it off.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's supporters George Luther Stearns, Franklin B.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Sanborn, Thomas Wentworth Higginson, Theodore Parker, Samuel Gridley Howe, and Gerrit Smith were all abolitionists, members of the so-called Secret Six who provided financial backing for Brown's raid.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's raid, says historian David Potter, "was meant to be of vast magnitude and to produce a revolutionary slave uprising throughout the South".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown hoped to have quickly a small army of runaway slaves, but made no provision to inform these potential runaways, although he got a little local support.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Army was dispatched to put down the raid, and Brown was quickly captured.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] He was tried for treason against the Commonwealth of Virginia, murder, and inciting a slave revolt, was found guilty of all charges, and was hanged.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At his trial, Brown exuded a remarkable zeal and single-mindedness that played directly to Southerners' worst fears.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under Virginia law there was a month between the sentencing and the hanging, and in those weeks Brown spoke gladly with reporters and anyone else who wanted to see him, and wrote many letters.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Few individuals did more to cause secession than John Brown, because Southerners believed he was right about an impending slave revolt.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The day of his execution, Brown prophesied, "the crimes of this guilty land will never be purged away but with blood.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War began with the stated goal of preserving the Union, and Lincoln said repeatedly that on the topic of slavery, he was only opposed to its spread to the Western territories.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This view of the war progressively changed, one step at a time, as public sentiment evolved, until by 1865 the war was seen in the North as primarily concerned with ending slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first federal act taken against slavery during the war occurred on 16 April 1862, when Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, which abolished slavery in Washington, D.C.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A few months later, on June 19, Congress banned slavery in all federal territories, fulfilling Lincoln's 1860 campaign promise.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of thousands of escaped slaves, achieving freedom, or so they hoped, by crossing Union lines.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, and thus did not have to be returned to their Confederate owners.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, effective 1 January 1863, which declared only those slaves in Confederate states to be free.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Colored Troops began operations in 1863.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Act of 1850 was repealed in June 1864.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually support for abolition was enough to pass the Thirteenth Amendment, ratified in December 1865, which abolished slavery everywhere in the United States, freeing more than 50,000 people still enslaved in Kentucky and Delaware, in 1865 the only states in which slavery still existed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Thirteenth Amendment also abolished slavery among the Native American tribes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement began about the time of the United States' independence.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first abolition organization was the Pennsylvania Abolition Society, which first met in 1775; Benjamin Franklin was its president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The New York Manumission Society was founded in 1785 by powerful politicians: John Jay, Alexander Hamilton, and Aaron Burr.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] There is quite a bit of confusion about when slavery was abolished in the Northern states, because "abolishing slavery" meant different things in different states.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] These included the first abolition laws in the entire New World: the Massachusetts Constitution, adopted in 1780, declared all men to have rights, making slavery unenforceable, and it disappeared through the individual actions of both masters and slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, what the abolition forces passed in 1799 in New York State was an Act for the *gradual* abolition of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery in New York did not officially end until 1827, and more than 70 enslaved people in New York appeared on the 1830 decennial census.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No slaves appeared in the state's 1840 census.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] New Jersey abolished slavery in 1804, but in 1860 a dozen black people were still held as "perpetual apprentices".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Northwest Ordinance of 1787, the Congress of the Confederation prohibited slavery in the territories northwest of the Ohio River.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the Constitutional Convention of 1787, slavery was the most contentious topic.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outright prohibition of slavery was impossible, because the Southern states (Georgia, South Carolina, North Carolina, Virginia, Maryland, and Delaware) would never have agreed to it.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The only restriction on slavery that was agreed to was to allow Congress to prohibit the importation of slaves, and even that was postponed for 20 years.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By that time, all the states except South Carolina had laws abolishing or severely limiting the importation of slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As he put it, this would "withdraw the citizens of the United States from all further participation in those violations of human rights...which the morality, the reputation, and the best of our country have long been eager to proscribe".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, about 1,000 slaves per year continued to be illegally brought (smuggled) into the United States; see Wanderer and Clotilda.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was primarily via Spanish Florida and the Gulf Coast; the United States acquired Florida from Spain in 1819, effective 1821, in part as a slave-control measure: no imports coming in, and certainly no fugitives escaping into a refuge.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress declined to pass any restriction on the lucrative interstate slave trade, which expanded to replace the supply of African slaves (see Slavery in the United States#Slave trade).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1776, Quaker and Moravian advocates helped persuade numerous slaveholders in the Upper South to free their slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Manumissions increased for nearly two decades.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many individual acts by slaveholders freed thousands of slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slaveholders freed slaves in such numbers that the percentage of free black people in the Upper South increased from 1 to 10 percent, with most of that increase in Virginia, Maryland and Delaware.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1810 three-quarters of blacks in Delaware were free.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most notable of men offering freedom was Robert Carter III of Virginia, who freed more than 450 people by "Deed of Gift", filed in 1791.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This number was more slaves than any single American had freed before or after.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Often slaveholders came to their decisions by their own struggles in the Revolution; their wills and deeds frequently cited language about the equality of men supporting the decision to set slaves free.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The era's changing economy also encouraged slaveholders to release slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Planters were shifting from labor-intensive tobacco to mixed-crop cultivation and needed fewer slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1860, 91.7% of the blacks in Delaware and 49.7% of those in Maryland were free.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Such early free families often formed the core of artisans, professionals, preachers, and teachers in future generations.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, this did not signal racial equality.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Though free from slavery, blacks still faced immense discrimination.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] For example, Delaware affirmed and reaffirmed black disenfranchisement several times throughout the late 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Delaware's General Assembly enacted harsh black codes throughout the 19th century that restricted travel, property ownership, expression, and socialization for African Americans.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The amendment failed and Missouri became a slave state.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian David Brion Davis, this may have been the first time in the world that a political leader openly attacked slavery's perceived legality in such a radical manner.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Postmaster General refused to allow the mails to carry abolition pamphlets to the South.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Northern teachers suspected of abolitionism were expelled from the South, and abolitionist literature was banned.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One Northerner, Amos Dresser (1812–1904), in 1835 was tried in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing anti-slavery publications, convicted, and as punishment was whipped publicly.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southerners rejected the denials of Republicans that they were abolitionists.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They pointed to John Brown's attempt in 1859 to start a slave uprising as proof that multiple Northern conspiracies were afoot to ignite slave rebellions.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Although some abolitionists did call for slave revolts, no evidence of any other Brown-like conspiracy has been discovered.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The North felt threatened as well, for as Eric Foner concludes, "northerners came to view slavery as the very antithesis of the good society, as well as a threat to their own fundamental values and interests".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The famous, "fiery" abolitionist Abby Kelley Foster, from Massachusetts, was considered an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in full civil rights for all black people.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She held to the view that the freed slaves would colonize Liberia.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Parts of the anti-slavery movement became known as "Abby Kellyism".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She recruited Susan B Anthony and Lucy Stone to the movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Effingham Capron, a cotton and textile scion, who attended the Quaker meeting where Abby Kelley Foster and her family were members, became a prominent abolitionist at the local, state, and national levels.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The local anti-slavery society at Uxbridge, Massachusetts, had more than 25% of the town's population as members.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] McPherson in 1964 defined an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He notes that many historians have used a broader definition without his emphasis on immediacy.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Thus he does not include opponents of slavery such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party; they called for the immediate end to expansion of slavery before 1861.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As such, abolitionism in the United States was identified by historians as an expression of moralism, it often operated in tandem with another social reform effort, the temperance movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was also attacked, to a lesser degree, as harmful on economic grounds.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evidence was that the South, with many enslaved African Americans on plantations, was definitely poorer than the North, which had few.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Historians and scholars have largely overlooked the work of black abolitionists; instead, they have focused on only a few black abolitionists, such as Frederick Douglass.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Yet lesser-known black abolitionists, such as Martin Delany and James Monroe Whitfield, also played an undeniably large role in shaping the movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionists had the distinct problem of having to confront an often-hostile American public, while still acknowledging their nationality and struggle.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As a result, many black abolitionists "intentionally adopted aspects of British, New England, and Midwestern cultures".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Furthermore, much of abolitionist rhetoric, and black abolitionist rhetoric in particular, were influenced by the Puritan preaching heritage.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Frederick Douglass was a notable black abolitionist, who significantly contributed to the transnational abolitionist movement through his lecture tours of the United Kingdom from 1845 to 1847.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In particular, he had a connection with Daniel O'Connell: Both O'Connell and Douglass strongly opposed slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] On 4 October 1845, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society gave Douglass a Bible bound in gold.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] African Americans, with Douglass being a key example, were involving themselves in US foreign relations and influencing British anti-slavery rhetoric.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass was best known for his speeches, and he completed 280 lectures across the UK and Ireland in the 19 months that he was there.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric discussed relationships between power, race, and the popular imagination, showing the complexities of the morality and representation of the abolitionist debate.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass and other black nationalists capitalised on pre-existing political and ideological debates among the UK to reassert the need for abolitionism.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In general, Black female abolitionists had separate motives and rhetorical strategies than White female abolitionists.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were often middle class and members of literary societies; the ones to which they belonged were often made up of solely Black women.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their activist efforts, they held themselves to high moral standards to be viewed as legitimate by others.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sarah Mapps Douglass, a free-born Quaker who wrote articles for *The Liberator* on abolition also served as the secretary for a literary society for women in Philadelphia, where she emphasized the importance of education and morality for Black women.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women that escaped slavery would sometimes write and publish their slave narratives as a way to argue for abolition.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In opposition to male slave narratives, like Frederick Douglass's, which highlighted literacy, Black women emphasized the communities and relationships they formed as keys to their humanity and right to freedom.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were also keen to highlight their relationship to motherhood, so as to emphasize their shared traits with white women and the ways in which they too could meet traditional expectations of white women.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Jacobs's *Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl* showcases her grandmother as the matriarch of her family, which shows how enslaved mothers are capable of nurturing like valued white women.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women also played their role in the abolitionist movement, both domestically and internationally, showing involvement in US Foreign Relations.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One notable example was Harriet Jacobs, who produced letters in England reflecting on her experiences as a slave in the US to challenge the pro-slavery movement in the USA.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The London Emancipation Committee published her letters into a book, titled: The Deeper Wrong: Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl, Written by Herself.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The book was not just noticed in reform journals, but in the mainstream press.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lengthy British reviews show how the book helped abolitionists win public support in Britain.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric could be done in literary form, a way for black women to have influence in an international abolitionist movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not only a transatlantic movement between Britain and the US, it also had influence in the Caribbean and South America.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1833 legal case Mundrucu v Barker also carried international importance in the abolitionist campaign.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In taking a stand against segregation, a black Brazilian immigrant had focused worldwide attention on racism in slaveholding US society.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Here there was division between white Philadelphians who saw black Saint Dominguan refugees as a threat to the city and country's racial order, their way of trying to justify slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This shows the connection between attitudes towards segregation and slavery helped shape black abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This led to domestic organisations being established by interracial communities, such as the Boston Female Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Working as Jamaican-based writers for New York newspapers between 1840 and 1851, the two black US-Jamaican brothers, Henry and George Davison provided inter-American perspectives on abolitionism.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Henry wrote letters to the National Anti-Slavery Standard.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black Americans had opportunities to write for newspapers, providing publicity and discussion of abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was moving beyond internal US divisions, but reaching influence outside of the USA.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not simply an African-American activity, but involved South American and Caribbean individuals too, showing an international movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina and Sarah Grimké were the first female anti-slavery agents, and played a variety of roles in the abolitionist movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though born in the South, the Grimké sisters became disillusioned with slavery and moved North to get away from it.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Perhaps because of their birthplace, the Grimké sisters' critiques carried particular weight and specificity.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina Grimké spoke of her thrill at seeing white men do manual labor of any kind.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their perspectives as native Southerners as well as women, brought a new important point of view to the abolitionist movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1836, they moved to New York and began work for the Anti-Slavery Society, where they met and were impressed by William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The sisters wrote many pamphlets (Angelina's "Appeal to the Christian Women of the South" was the only appeal directly to Southern women to defy slavery laws) and played leadership roles at the first Anti-Slavery Convention of American Women in 1837.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimkés later made a notable speaking tour around the north, which culminated in Angelina's February 1838 address to a Committee of the Legislature of Massachusetts.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lucretia Mott was also active in the abolitionist movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though well known for her women's suffrage advocacy, Mott also played an important role in the abolitionist movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] During four decades, she delivered sermons about abolitionism, women's rights, and a host of other issues.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott acknowledged her Quaker beliefs' determinative role in affecting her abolitionist sentiment.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster, with a strong Quaker heritage, helped lead Susan B.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony and Lucy Stone into the abolition movement, and encouraged them to take on a role in political activism.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] the first National Women's Rights Convention, held in Worcester, Massachusetts, in 1850.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The better-known Seneca Falls Convention, held in 1848, was not national).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She was an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in immediate and complete civil rights for all slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 1841, however, she had resigned from the Quakers over disputes about not allowing anti-slavery speakers in meeting houses (including the Uxbridge monthly meeting where she had attended with her family), and the group disowned her.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley became a leading speaker and the leading fundraiser for the American Anti-slavery Society.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Radical abolitionism became known as "Abby Kelleyism".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Other leaders in the abolitionist movement were Lydia Maria Child, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Susan B.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony, Harriet Tubman, and Sojourner Truth.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But even beyond these well-known women, abolitionism maintained impressive support from white middle-class and some black women.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was these women who performed many of the logistical, day-to-day tasks that made the movement successful.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They raised money, wrote and distributed propaganda pieces, drafted and signed petitions, and lobbied the legislatures.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though abolitionism sowed the seeds of the women's rights movement, most women became involved in abolitionism because of a gendered religious worldview, and the idea that they had feminine, moral responsibilities.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in the winter of 1831–1832, women sent three petitions to the Virginia legislature, advocating emancipation of the state's slave population.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The only precedent for such action was Catharine Beecher's organization of a petition protesting the Cherokee removal.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Virginia petitions, while the first of their kind, were by no means the last.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Similar backing increased leading up to the Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even as women played crucial roles in abolitionism, the movement simultaneously helped stimulate women's-rights efforts.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A full 10 years before the Seneca Falls Convention, the Grimké sisters were travelling and lecturing about their experiences with slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As Gerda Lerner says, the Grimkés understood their actions' great impact.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "In working for the liberation of the slave," Lerner writes, "Sarah and Angelina Grimké found the key to their own liberation.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And the consciousness of the significance of their actions was clearly before them.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women gained important experiences in public speaking and organizing that stood them in good stead going forward.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimké sisters' public speaking played a critical part in legitimizing women's place in the public sphere.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Some Christian women created cent societies to benefit abolition movements, where many women in a church would each pledge to donate one cent a week to help abolitionist causes.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even though women were not allowed full access to political and religious spaces, they still played a big role in the abolitionist movement through both public activism and behind-the-scenes activism.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As historian Julie Roy Jeffrey explains, a lot of women relied on their religious faith and authority to speak out against slavery and challenge male-led church systems that tried to keep them quiet.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They believed slavery went against Christian values and saw it as a deep moral wrong.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their speeches and writing, they made it clear that true faith could not exist alongside a system that discriminated against people.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women like Sarah Otis Ernst and Maria Child used persuasive writing, public speeches, and organizing work to fight not just slavery, but also the powerful systems that kept it going.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Ernst was a strong Garrisonian who got frustrated when mainstream abolitionists started watering down their message.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She did not like that people in the movement were trying to be more politically strategic instead of sticking to the original beliefs, like full racial equality, immediate emancipation, and refusing to work with pro-slavery systems.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the 1852 American and Foreign Antislavery Society convention, around two-thirds of the 2,000 people there were women.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] That says a lot about how involved women were, even though they often got written out of the story.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not vote, but they used writing, speeches, and journalism to influence politics and public opinion.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their activism was real, public, and tied directly into national conversations.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But not all women approached the movement the same way.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There were clear differences between how white and Black women operated, and sometimes those differences caused conflict.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women, especially ones who were more religious, focused a lot on the moral and spiritual arguments.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They used Christian values to call out slavery as a sin and tried to appeal to other white Americans by framing it as a moral crisis.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Lydia Maria Child wrote about Christian duty and compassion to get people on board.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But that type of activism did not always connect with what Black women were facing every day.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And even inside the abolitionist circles, Black women were still often pushed to the side.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not always given speaking time, leadership roles, or space in published work.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sojourner Truth had to fight just to speak at some events, and even then, people questioned her.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women could usually speak and be heard if they used moral language.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women had to work twice as hard just to get into the room.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They faced racism from inside the movement and also from the outside world, which made it even harder for their voices to be heard.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Richmond talks about how central Black women were to abolition, even though they have been left out of most of the history.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Women like Sojourner Truth, Maria Stewart, and Harriet Tubman struggled not only for the abolition of slavery but for gender and racial equality as well".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not just giving speeches, they were founding antislavery groups, organizing communities, and building transatlantic networks.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were working through both racism and sexism and still finding ways to be powerful voices.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Truth's line "Ain’t I a Woman?" and Stewart saying she had to "stand for justice wherever I find it" show how they were calling out not just slavery, but the whole system that tried to silence them.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Tubman took a different route; she led people to freedom through the Underground Railroad and even worked for the Union Army.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women's abolitionism looked different from that of white women.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was rooted in their personal experience and often more direct and action-focused.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They made sure the fight for abolition was not just about ending slavery, but also about achieving full equality and justice.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The July 1848 Seneca Falls Convention grew out of a partnership between Lucretia Mott and Elizabeth Cady Stanton that blossomed while the two worked, at first, on abolitionist issues.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Indeed, the two met at the World's Anti-Slavery Convention in the summer of 1840.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott brought oratorical skills and an impressive reputation as an abolitionist to the nascent women's rights movement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism brought together active women and enabled them to make political and personal connections while honing communication and organizational skills.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even Sojourner Truth, commonly associated with abolitionism, delivered her first documented public speech at the 1850 National Women's Rights Convention in Worcester.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There, she argued for women's reform activism.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The religious component of American abolitionism was great.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It began with the Quakers, then moved to the other Protestants with the Second Great Awakening of the early 19th century.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Saying slavery was sinful made its evil easy to understand, and tended to arouse fervor for the cause.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The debate about slavery was often based on what the Bible said or did not say about it.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John Brown, who had studied the Bible for the ministry, proclaimed that he was "an instrument of God".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Second Great Awakening of the 1820s and 1830s in religion inspired groups that undertook many types of social reform.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For some that included the immediate abolition of slavery as they considered it sinful to hold slaves as well as to tolerate slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Opposition to slavery, for example, was one of the works of piety of the Methodist Churches, which were established by John Wesley.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Abolitionist" had several meanings at the time.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The followers of William Lloyd Garrison, including Wendell Phillips and Frederick Douglass, demanded the "immediate abolition of slavery", hence the name, also called "immediatism".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A more pragmatic group of abolitionists, such as Theodore Weld and Arthur Tappan, wanted immediate action, but were willing to support a program of gradual emancipation, with a long intermediate stage.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The *True Wesleyan* a periodical founded by Orange Scott and Jotham Horton was used to disseminate abolitionist views.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Methodist and Quaker branches of Christianity played an integral part in the formulation of abolitionist ideology in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Anti-slavery men", such as John Quincy Adams, did not call slavery a sin.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They called it an evil feature of society as a whole.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They did what they could to limit slavery and end it where possible, but were not part of any abolitionist group.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in 1841, John Quincy Adams represented the *Amistad* African slaves in the Supreme Court of the United States and argued that they should be set free.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the last years before the war, "anti-slavery" could refer to the Northern majority, such as Abraham Lincoln, who opposed expansion of slavery or its influence, as by the Kansas–Nebraska Act or the Fugitive Slave Act.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many Southerners called all these abolitionists, without distinguishing them from the Garrisonians.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics in the United States seldom challenged the role of slavery in society as it was protected at that time by the U.S.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They viewed the abolitionists as anti-Catholic and anti-Irish.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics were generally well received by Democrats in the South.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, most Irish Nationalists and Fenians supported the abolition of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Daniel O'Connell, the Catholic leader of the Irish in Ireland, supported abolition in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He organized a petition in Ireland with 60,000 signatures urging the Irish of the United States to support abolition.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John O'Mahony, a founder of the Irish Republican Brotherhood was an abolitionist and served as colonel in the 69th Infantry Regiment during the Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Irish Catholics in the United States were recent immigrants; most were poor and very few owned slaves.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They had to compete with free blacks for unskilled labor jobs.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They saw abolitionism as the militant wing of evangelical anti-Catholic Protestantism.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Catholic Church in the United States had long ties in slaveholding Maryland and Louisiana.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1861, the Archbishop of New York wrote to Secretary of War Cameron: "That the Church is opposed to slavery ...
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Her doctrine on that subject is, that it is a crime to reduce men naturally free to a condition of servitude and bondage, as slaves." No American bishop supported extra-political abolition or interference with states' rights before the Civil War.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The secular Germans of the Forty-Eighter immigration were largely anti-slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Prominent Forty-Eighters included Carl Schurz and Friedrich Hecker.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] German Lutherans seldom took a position on slavery, but German Methodists were anti-slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Both Garrison's newspaper *The Liberator* and his book *Thoughts on African Colonization* (1832) arrived shortly after publication at Western Reserve College, in Hudson, Ohio, which was briefly the center of abolitionist discourse in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (John Brown grew up in Hudson.) The readers, including college president Charles Backus Storrs, found Garrison's arguments and evidence convincing.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolition versus colonization rapidly became the primary issue on the campus, to the point that Storrs complained in writing that nothing else was being discussed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The college's chaplain and theology professor Beriah Green said that "his *Thoughts* and his paper (*The Liberator*) are worthy of the eye and the heart of every American." Green delivered in the college chapel in November and December 1832 four sermons supporting immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These so offended the college's trustees, more conservative than either the students or the faculty, that Green resigned, expecting that he would be fired.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Elizur Wright, another professor, resigned soon afterwards and became the first secretary of the American Anti-Slavery Society, of which Green was the first president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Storrs contracted tuberculosis, took a leave of absence, and died within six months.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This left the school with only one of its four professors.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Green was soon hired as the new president of the Oneida Institute.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under the previous president, George Washington Gale, there had been a mass walkout of students; among the issues was Gale's lack of support for abolition.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He accepted the position on conditions that 1) he be allowed to preach "immediatism", immediate emancipation, and 2) that African-American students be admitted on the same terms as white students.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These were accepted, and we know the names of 16 Blacks who studied there.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Native American students, of whom we know the names of two, were openly accepted as well.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under Green, Oneida became "a hotbed of anti-slavery activity." It was "abolitionist to the core, more so than any other American college." For Presbyterian minister and Bible professor Green, slavery was not just an evil but a sin, and abolitionism was what Christ's principles mandated.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under him a cadre of abolitionists was trained, who then carried the abolitionist message, via lectures and sermons, throughout the North.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many future well-known black leaders and abolitionists were students at Oneida while Green was president.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These include William Forten (son of James Forten), Alexander Crummell, Rev.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Oneida Institute did not have an incident, like that of Western Reserve, which brought national attention to it.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Its successor, Lane Seminary, in Cincinnati, did.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Lane was Oneida moved west." Leading the exodus from Oneida was a former Oneida student, and private student of Gale before that, Theodore Dwight Weld.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He greatly impressed the philanthropist brothers and abolitionists Arthur and Lewis Tappan.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They hired him to report on the movement nationally, and specifically to find a new location for their funding, since Oneida, a manual labor school, was a disappointment, according to Weld and his student followers.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the same time that Weld was scouting a location for a new school, the barely-functioning Lane Seminary was looking for students.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Based on Weld's recommendation, the Tappans started giving Lane the financial support they had previously given Oneida.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld, though on paper enrolled as a student at Lane, was de facto its head, choosing, through his recommendations to the Tappans, the president (Lyman Beecher, after Charles Grandison Finney, who became later the second president of Oberlin, turned it down), and telling the trustees whom to hire.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The group of students led by Weld constituted the first student movement in the history of the country.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He chose Lane, and they followed him there.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When he soon left Lane for another new, struggling institution, Oberlin, they did so too, as a group.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Students, many of whom considered him the real leader of Lane, responded to Weld's announcement of the new school in Cincinnati.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lane ended up with about 100 students, the most of any seminary in America.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One of Weld's key contentions (and of Puritan abolition sentiment in general) was that slavery was inherently anti-family.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] While slave marriage was illegal, it happened frequently.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners expected their slaves to have many children to replace their numbers; Virginia and Maryland "exported" slaves to the Deep South—they were an asset like cattle—after Congress had banned the importation of slaves in 1808.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since slaves were property they were frequently bought and sold, ripping apart families.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In his 1839 book *American Slavery as It Is*, Weld showed just how brutal the slave trade was towards families.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] To the very family-focused Puritans, this was one of the greatest crimes of slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld's descriptions of families destroyed would later serve as the basis for scenes in *Uncle Tom's Cabin*, including Uncle Tom's being sold and separated from the children.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] No sooner had this disparate group of former Oneida students and others arrived at Lane, under the leadership of Weld, than they formed an anti-slavery society.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They then proceeded to hold a well-publicized series of debates on abolition versus African colonization, lasting 18 evenings, and decided that abolition was a much better solution to slavery.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In fact no real debate took place, since no one appeared to defend colonization.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These "debates", which were well publicized, alarmed Lane's president Lyman Beecher and the school's trustees.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Adding to their alarm were the classes the students were holding in the Black community, teaching Blacks to read.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Fearing violence, since Cincinnati was strongly anti-abolitionist (see Cincinnati riots of 1829), they immediately prohibited any future such "off-the-topic" discussions and activities.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The students, again led by Weld, felt that abolitionism was so important – it was their responsibility as Christians to promote it – and they resigned *en masse*, joined by Asa Mahan, a trustee who supported the students.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] With support from the Tappans, they briefly tried to establish a new seminary, but as this did not prove a practical solution they accepted a proposal that they move as a group to the new Oberlin Collegiate Institute.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to its students' anti-slavery position, Oberlin soon became one of the most liberal colleges and accepted African-American students.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Along with Garrison, Northcutt and Collins were proponents of immediate abolition.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster became an "ultra abolitionist" and a follower of William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony as well as Elizabeth Cady Stanton into the anti-slavery cause.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] After 1840, "abolition" usually referred to positions similar to Garrison's.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was largely an ideological movement led by about 3,000 people, including free blacks and free people of color, many of whom, such as Frederick Douglass in Rochester, New York, and Robert Purvis and James Forten in Philadelphia, played prominent leadership roles.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass became legally free during a two-year stay in England, as British supporters raised funds to purchase his freedom from his American owner Thomas Auld, and also helped fund his abolitionist newspapers in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism had a strong religious base including Quakers, and people converted by the revivalist fervor of the Second Great Awakening, led by Charles Finney in the North, in the 1830s.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Belief in abolition contributed to the formation of Christian denominations, such as the Free Methodist Church.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evangelical abolitionists founded some colleges, most notably Bates College in Maine and Oberlin College in Ohio.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement attracted such figures as Yale president Noah Porter and Harvard president Thomas Hill.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the mid nineteenth century, American abolitionism was shaped by British ideological and organisational influences.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A key part of this exchange was the intersection of abolitionism and free trade ideology.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] British reformers such as Richard Cobden and the Anti Corn Law League inspired American abolitionists to promote free trade arguing that it was morally and economically aligned to abolition in the United States.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Leaders like Joshua Leavitt, campaigner for the Liberty Party, argued that repealing British tariffs would reduce US reliance on Southern slave grown cotton and open markets to free labour goods from the North.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another prominent British activist was George Thompson, who toured the US several times where he delivered speeches connecting Free Trade to the American abolition cause.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Figures like Cobden and Thompson were a direct influence on the ideology of Lloyd Garrison.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another movement called the Free-produce movement extended across the Atlantic.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This movement aimed to boycott goods produced by enslaved Africans.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement was connected to British activist Joseph Sturge and the idea that a free market allowed for consumer morality.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sociologist Cecilia Walsh-Russo developed the term 'mutual brokerage' to refer to the interchange of ideas within UK-US abolitionist movements.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She refers to the interactions which allowed ideas and political strategy to co-develop, rather than suggesting one learned from the other.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Walsh-Russo cites the 1840 World Anti-Slavery Convention in London as an example of mutual brokerage.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She claims the exclusion of women as delegates, despite their presence at the events forced transatlantic abolitionist to re-assess their understanding of political participation and democracy, often leading to more progressive views in UK and US activism.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Despite exclusion from the conference women asserted their right to participate in the abolitionist cause by using informal setting such as salons to promote abolition.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] William Lloyd Garrison also engaged in Irish politics.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He communicated with key figures like Daniel O'Connell, which shaped his understanding of abolition as 'universal emancipation'.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonian abolitionists also used Ireland and the Irish as tools of comparison especially in combatting the American Colonization Society.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] However, efforts to forge direct relations between Irish Americans and African Americans largely failed.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1842 Address from the People of Ireland to Their Countrymen and Countrywomen in America, written by Irish abolitionists and signed by O'Connell, urged Irish Americans to support abolition and racial equality.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonians hoped this would foster diasporic responsibility among the Irish but it was rejected by most.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish immigrants, perhaps due to a desire to assimilate in the US, were overall not supportive of the abolitionist cause.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It is easy to overstate the support for abolitionism in the North.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of white Southerners, though by no means all, supported slavery; there was a growing feeling in favor of emancipation in North Carolina, Maryland, Virginia, and Kentucky, until the panic resulting from Nat Turner's 1831 revolt put an end to it.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But only a minority in the North supported abolition, seen as an extreme, "radical" measure.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (See Radical Republicans.) Horace Greeley remarked in 1854 that he had "never been able to discover any strong, pervading, over-ruling Anti Slavery sentiment in the Free States." Free blacks were subject in the North as well as in the South to conditions almost inconceivable today (2019).
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Although the picture is neither uniform nor static, in general free blacks in the North were not citizens and could neither vote nor hold public office.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not give testimony in court and their word was never taken against a white man's word, as a result of which white crimes against blacks were rarely punished.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black children could not study in the public schools, even though Black taxpayers helped support them, and there were only a handful of schools for Black students, like the African Free School in New York, the Abiel Smith School in Boston, and the Watkins Academy for Negro Youth in Baltimore.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When schools for negroes were set up in Ohio in the 1830s, the teacher of one slept in it every night "for fear whites would burn it", and at another, "a vigilance committee threatened to tar and feather [the teacher] and ride her on a rail if she did not leave".
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (Oberlin Collegiate Institute was the first college that survived to admit them by policy; the Oneida Institute was a short-lived predecessor.) In wages, housing, access to services, and transportation, separate but equal or Jim Crow treatment would have been a great improvement.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The proposal to create the country's first college for negros, in New Haven, Connecticut, got such strong local opposition (New Haven Excitement) that it was quickly abandoned.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Schools in which blacks and whites studied together in Canaan, New Hampshire, and Canterbury, Connecticut, were physically destroyed by mobs.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The prosecutor was Francis Scott Key.) In Savannah, Georgia, the mayor and alderman protected an abolitionist visitor from a mob.
[src:abolitionism-in-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the North there was far more serious violence by mobs, what the press sometimes called "mobocracy".
